The President of Russia Vladimir Putin signed the law on the introduction of administrative responsibility for violation of the term and procedure for payment of goods (works, services) in the procurement for state and municipal needs.
This law is intended to address the very acute problem of non-compliance of customers with their obligations in the implementation of public and municipal procurement.
Two years ago, the situation when entrepreneurs could not receive payment under already fulfilled state and municipal contracts was ubiquitous.
At the same time, the President of Russia instructed the Prosecutor General of the Russian Federation to take the problem under special control.
Because the businessmen themselves could not cope with unscrupulous customers who entered into unfunded contracts, tried in every way to evade the obligations on payment and included illegal terms in the contracts.
The problem was systemic throughout the country.
Since 2015, in order to protect the rights of entrepreneurs to receive payment for public orders, the Prosecutor’s Office has submitted 9,700 submissions, according to the results of their consideration, 4,500 officials have been brought to disciplinary responsibility, 533 have been brought to administrative responsibility, 75 submissions have been submitted to the investigative bodies for the organization of procedural inspections, 46 of them have been opened criminal cases.
As a result, the debt to entrepreneurs in the amount of more than 66 billion rubles was repaid.
And these huge sums were not accumulated as a result of the non-payment of multibillion-dollar contracts.
To fabulous debts led to numerous, systematic delays in payment of services to entrepreneurs for much more modest amounts.
Here is a typical case.
The head of a small company won a tender for the provision of social transportation services for several million rubles.
The man invested all his working capital, fully fulfilled his obligations, but he did not receive the money on time.
The result is a growing financial pile of debts on wages, taxes, loans, which would have led to bankruptcy if the entrepreneur had not sought help from the prosecutor’s office.
In some regions, the problem has been eliminated as much as possible.
However, as of the first half of 2017, the total amount of debt under state and municipal contracts, identified by prosecutors of the constituent entities of the Russian Federation, amounted to about 27.4 billion rubles.
In regions where debt indicators continue to reach critical values, the prosecutor’s office operates in the mode of manual crisis management.
The Attorney-General personally holds out-of-town meetings with representatives of the local authorities, during which all violations discovered by prosecutors are thoroughly examined and measures are taken to remedy them promptly.
Such operational meetings have already been held in Yaroslavl and Yekaterinburg this year.
The implementation of the Federal Law No. 189-FZ "On Amendments to the Code of the Russian Federation on Administrative Offences in Regard to Establishing the Administrative Responsibility of the Customer's Officials for Violation of the Term and Procedure for Payment for Goods (Works, Services) in Purchasing to Ensure State and Municipal Needs" will be able to qualitatively improve the payment discipline of public customers, which was signed last week by the President of Russia.
The draft law was developed by the Ministry of Economic Development of Russia at the initiative of the Prosecutor General’s Office.
The new law will supplement the Code of Administrative Offences of the Russian Federation with an article that provides for a fine of 30 thousand to 50 thousand rubles for violation by an official of the customer of the period and procedure for payment of goods, works and services in state and municipal procurement.
And if an official has already been subjected to administrative punishment for a similar offence, he will be disqualified for a period of one to two years.
All prosecutors of the subjects of the Russian Federation have already been instructed to ensure the application of these legislative novelties in practice.
Civil Rights Advocacy Group Announces Traffic Warning in Missouri
The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People has issued a warning to people of color traveling to Missouri because of the state’s discriminatory policies and racist attacks.
The group’s statement reads: “The National Association for the Advancement of Colored Travellers’ Warning, valid until August 28, 2017, urges African-American travelers, visitors and Missouri citizens to be particularly cautious and cautious when traveling across the state due to a number of dubious incidents and racist backgrounds.”
According to the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People, the movement warning was prompted by a recent Missouri law that made it harder for people to win lawsuits related to discrimination, as well as the state’s law enforcement agencies disproportionately targeting minorities.
“Your people are being subjected to human rights violations.
They are stopped on roads because of their skin color, beaten and killed,” Rod Chapel, president of the Missouri National Association for the Advancement of Colored People, told the Kansas City Star.
“We hear complaints more often than ever before.”
This is the first warning of its kind issued by the organization against the state of the United States.
The group cited incidents such as the racial humiliation of black students at the University of Missouri and the death of 28-year-old Tory Sanders, a black man from Tennessee.
Sanders was killed in suspicious circumstances earlier this year after running out of gas while on a state trip, and the Missouri State Police arrested him without charging him with a crime.
The warning also mentions a recent report by the Missouri Attorney General’s Office that black drivers are 75 percent more likely to be stopped on the road than white drivers.
“The purpose of the warning is to keep people aware of the situation and alert their relatives and friends and colleagues about what might happen in Missouri,” Chapel said.
“People need to be prepared one way or another, whether they take the bail money with them or tell their relatives that they are traveling through the state.”
According to the latest data from the FBI’s hate crime reporting program, Missouri recorded 100 hate crimes in 2015, making it the sixteenth state to report hate crimes.
The move warning is also a response to a new Missouri law that will make it harder to prosecute a legal entity for housing or employment discrimination.
Earlier, the American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) issued warnings to travelers in Texas and Arizona after those states enacted new immigration control laws that required local law enforcement agencies to arrest people for violating immigration laws, which the ACLU said was meant to increase the number of racial checks.
Traffic warnings are usually issued by the State Department in relation to other countries, but recently public organizations have resorted to this measure in response to certain laws and trends within the United States.
