Nothing sacred?
The Trump White House is now targeting the Statue of Liberty.
The most reliable sign of a regime change is when it starts fighting with statues.
Americans understand this no worse than everyone else - hence the deliberate theatrical demolition of the statue of Saddam Hussein in Firdos Square in Baghdad in 2003.
Steven Miller, one of the Trump administration’s key ideologues, no doubt knew what he was doing when he carried a symbolic axe over the Statue of Liberty during a bitter argument with CNN journalist Jim Acosta about the president’s proposals to drastically reduce legal migration.
Let's be honest, Miller didn't try the statue itself.
Hordes of boat owners and artists depicting the Statue of Liberty would have lynched him if he had tried.
But he infringed on its meaning, and especially on the meaning that was attributed to it in 1903, 17 years after the completion of the monument, when poems by Emma Lazarus were added to the pedestal.
As Miller moaned at Acosta, “I don’t want to go deep into history here, but the Statue of Liberty is... a symbol of American freedom that illuminates the world.
The poem you are referring to was added later and is not part of the original Statue of Liberty.
Miller put the facts right, but as he said, it’s not really about the story.
It is about the current sound of the striking words of Lazarus, the only one in which the state invites not any immigrants, but the poorest: "Your tired, your poor, / your crowds dreaming to breathe freely / The unhappy garbage of your abundant shores."
Never before have "unfortunate garbage" been so visible on our screens.
Miller did not do literature studies - he made it clear that in America these people are not waiting for Trump.
This controversy about the meaning of the statue is part of a broader political and cultural war: it is indeed a controversy about the meaning of America.
Lazarus - and her friends who fought to put her words on the pedestal of the statue after her death - knew very well that they were committing a completely political act.
The sculpture was designed to mark the connection between the French and American republics with the help of a banal classical figure - the female image of Freedom.
Lazarus changed her meaning: in her poem, the female figure is no longer abstract, she has a voice.
And she got a completely different name: Mother of the Exiled.
The combination of the poem and the image was a brilliant feminist move and a crushing attack against American nativism.
And how Lazarus changed the meaning of the statue, the right though changed it back.
The loud Rush Limbaugh, a kind of John the Baptist who announced Trump’s arrival, argued in 2010 that Freedom does not invite anyone, rather it is an early neoconservative carrying the flames of America to a world lying in darkness: “Freedom is moving forward.
It carries the torch of freedom from the United States to the rest of the world.
The torch is not needed to illuminate the way to the United States.”
Contrary to the usual Limbo really hit the point here.
The meaning of the statue depends solely on the angle of view.
The great creative achievement of Lazarus was to see her as she would be seen by the exhausted, unhappy but hopeful people on the decks of ships after a long and often heavy voyage.
It means literally looking at the world through the eyes of people who are seeking refuge and a chance for a better life.
Her statue responds to them with the words of hope and hospitality they dream of hearing.
And, of course, that’s not the kind of perspective that Miller and Trump will ever want to acknowledge.
Their torch is needed not to illuminate the path, but to incite hatred, which is the only source of their power.
