Facebook Critics Block: Don’t run for public office unless you’re willing to listen to voter criticism
The founder of our country understood what a critical press was.
Americans loved George Washington, but that didn’t stop them from criticizing him for everything from domestic politics to his political principles.
Criticism, of course, annoyed him.
But he did not shut his mouth to his critics.
As Washington said in 1783, “Freedom of speech can be taken away and we, the deaf and the mute, will be led like sheep to the slaughterhouse.”
I will now turn to Maryland Governor Larry Hogan, who should try to be more like Washington.
Hogan’s subordinates blocked and deleted posts of at least 450 people who expressed their opinion on his official Facebook page.
And this week, the American Civil Liberties Union sued him for it.
The governor's subordinates called the lawsuit null and void, and the commentary on the Internet was written in the spirit of "well what".
“It’s just Facebook,” many will say.
But it's also important.
And this is especially important when it comes to a guy like Hogan.
He is a surprisingly popular Republican governor in a predominantly democratic state.
He is in second place in the approval rating among the 50 governors of the country.
Hogan is not a stubborn reactionary.
He has shown a firm hand in governing the state and a commitment to his principles.
He also deftly uses Facebook as his primary way of communicating with his constituents, and with jokes on his page shows his bald head after chemotherapy.
Therefore, blocking people who come to the governor’s page – which is declared as an official public forum and is run by administration employees with taxpayer money – is unnecessary and ultimately harmful.
In an interview with the Washington Post, spokeswoman Amelia Chess defended the governor’s actions, arguing that blocking comments was simply moderation.
But it’s too easy to use the image of trolls, spammers, and haters nagging on the Internet.
The Post has spoken to some of the real people who were blocked by Hogan.
And these are real people, not trolls - a teacher, a businessman, a pastor, who turn to their chosen leaders.
All of them say that their comments were respectful, meaningful and not rude.
The pastor quoted the Bible, appealing to the fact that Hogan is a Catholic.
Lakshmi’s lawyer, Sarma Ramana, from Bowie, Maryland, did not express hatred, but asked about hate crimes.
“I wrote a polite commentary that I was disappointed by his lack of reaction to hate crimes and other recent news,” she wrote in the comments section of the article.
“I also don’t like the idea that when a lot of people leave comments on the same topic, some immediately say it’s a so-called hoax, instead of admitting they’re dealing with a large group of disgruntled citizens.”
What the governor’s subordinates call a “concentrated spam attack,” others would probably call an “active lifestyle.”
In the era of Facebook, it’s easy to edit your image by simply blocking critics or deleting negative comments.
This is a far less dusty job than before, when it required sending people, collecting and burning newspapers with critical headlines, or arresting and shutting up protesters.
But that’s exactly what’s happening now, only in numbers.
Hogen is not the first official to be criticized for not wanting to listen to Facebook and other social networks.
President Trump has been sued by Twitter users who have been banned from his Twitter account.
One of the first, pivotal decisions on this topic was made this week in Virginia.
According to U.S. District Judge James K. Casheris, the chairman of the Laudon County Supervisory Board violated the First Amendment by banning a voter from his Facebook account.
And in Kentucky, Republican Governor Matt Bavin was sued by the American Civil Liberties Union for his behavior on Facebook and Twitter.
It shouldn't be that hard.
In Washington’s time, the era of affordable postal spending was about the same as the Internet is today.
From 1776 to 1800, the number of newspapers quadrupled, and the authors of anonymous letters severely undermined his authority.
Even then, Washington was dealing with anonymous trolls.
People under the pseudonyms of "Yuricola", "Valerius", "Belizarius" and "Portius" wrote letters to newspapers ridiculing Washington's decision.
According to historical documents compiled by the George Washington Papers online project, his office was flooded with petitions criticizing his position on the Treaty of Friendship, Trade and Navigation.
But he wasn’t trying to silence them.
Freedom of speech, dissent and speech is at the very foundation of our state.
And true leadership means agreeing to it.
