Poverty and death in Indonesia’s “golden land”
Bardina Degei does not use the stove when preparing dinner.
She seldom even uses the pot.
In her wooden house in Enarotali, the capital of Paniai County in the rebellious Indonesian province of Papua, a housewife usually just puts the sweet potato, which here is called a "note", right into the hearth.
After half an hour, the charred tuber is removed and eaten with impatient, unwashed hands.
Degei sits on the ground floor – she has no furniture – and it is here that she does her housework, such as washing clothes with muddy water from a nearby swamp.
The bathroom serves as a bucket in a room without a roof.
She is the youngest of her husband's four wives, and therefore she was not commissioned to work in the field.
Polygamy is common here.
Of course, working late can be dangerous: many men in this village are unemployed, many drink, and there are soldiers.
“No one dares to walk around the village after five o’clock in the evening,” she says.
It is a rare opportunity to look at everyday life in the highlands of Papua, a former Dutch colony that was annexed to Indonesia in 1969 after a dubious referendum when only 1,026 elders were forced to vote, publicly raising their hands in front of occupying troops.
The existing pro-independence movement quickly turned its anger against the Jakarta government, which maintains tight control of the region by preventing foreign journalists and human rights defenders.
In 2003, the province was officially divided into Papua and West Papua, and the independent state of Papua New Guinea occupies the eastern part of the island.
Enarotali is a city as remote as an abandoned one; the road here includes an hour and a half flight from Jayapura, the provincial capital, to Nabira, and then a five-hour car ride.
There is no public transport here.
The city with a population of about 19,000 people consists of wooden houses surrounded by bamboo fences; the roofs of corrugated steel are painted with rust in a variety of reddish shades.
Few Indonesians have made it, let alone journalists, and almost none of the foreigners.
Before the arrival of the Christian missionaries, the Papuans worshipped a god named Uga Tameya.
There were other changes.
“It was unusual for us to wear these clothes,” says Degei, pointing to his bright, hand-woven turban, dark skirt and bright shirt.
“We used to wear only leaves on our bodies.”
Papua is Indonesia’s poorest province, with 28% of its population living below the poverty line, and child mortality and literacy rates among the worst in Asia.
It is also Indonesian gold.
The world’s largest and most lucrative gold mine, Grasberg, owned by Phoenix-based Freeport McMoran, is just sixty miles from Paniai, a high-altitude province roughly the size of New Jersey, home to 153,000 people.
In 2015 alone, Freeport mined about $3.1 billion worth of gold and copper here.
In addition, Papua boasts forest reserves, the value of which is estimated at 78 billion dollars.
These riches, however, entail one misfortune for the Papuans, ensuring that Indonesia’s powerful armed forces retain their suffocating presence here.
According to a 2005 New York Times investigation, between 1998 and 2004, Freeport paid nearly $20 million to local troops and units, including up to $150,000 to one officer.
The demands for greater autonomy on the part of the Papuans threaten the existence of this goldmine and are ruthlessly suppressed.
According to human rights activists, more than 500,000 Papuans have been killed by Indonesian military forces since 1969, and thousands more have been raped, tortured and imprisoned.
According to the Asian Commission on Human Rights, the massacres in the indigenous highlands of Papua in the 1970s can be considered genocide.
Last year alone, Indonesian police arrested more than 3,900 peaceful protesters in the region.
“We will lose everything,” a report published in 2016 by the Diocese of Brisbane, contains evidence of atrocities committed in the previous year, such as executions without trial, torture – particularly frequent, as claimed in another report, rape and electric shocks – and the brutal suppression of peaceful demonstrations.
“It’s hard to count the number of casualties because incidents happen every week,” says Andreas Harsono, a researcher in Indonesia for Human Rights Watch.
The nuts tightened as Papua’s resources attracted an influx of displaced people from other parts of Indonesia.
The province’s 3.5-million-strong population is 83% Christian, but demographics change as Muslim economic migrants arrive from densely populated Indonesian islands of Java, Sumatra and Sulawesi.
Javanese shops, "warungi", sell fried chicken and a mixture of "gado-gado" vegetables served with peanut sauce.
Locals are trying to keep up with the competition.
“Migrants started selling chicken and vegetables in the traditional market cheaper than the natives of Papua,” explains Abet You, a 24-year-old native of Paniai, who moved to Jayapura, the provincial capital, because of work.
“Because of this, the indigenous people of Papua — the mother-mother (women) of Papua — have lost their sales market.”
Indonesian President Joko Widodo, popularly known as Jokowi, vowed to address inequality and rights abuses in Papua during his 2014 presidential campaign.
On his way to the Presidential Palace in Jakarta, the former carpenter enlisted the support of 27 of Papua’s 29 counties, including Paniai.
But in Papua, almost nothing has changed, and the locals feel loyal.
“Our hearts are broken because in 2014 we voted for Jokovi, expecting him to fulfill our hopes for justice,” says You.
In fact, just two months after Jokovi's October inauguration, Paniai survived the tragedy.
On December 7, 2014, a group of 11 children were out on the street singing Christmas hymns at a bonfire in Enarotali when two Indonesian soldiers broke out of the darkness on a motorcycle.
The frightened children told them to turn on the headlights.
Local pastor Javedt Tebay said one of the soldiers was offended by their tone and returned with four soldiers.
According to victims and eyewitnesses, soldiers who were drunk chased the children and beat them with rifle butts.
Then one of the soldiers shot at a group of children.
One child, 16-year-old Julianus Aimo, was so badly beaten that he fell into a coma.
A few hours later, someone set fire to a government election commission building nearby, and the next day the situation escalated.
About a thousand Papuan men, women and children gathered on a football field in front of a local police station and military command center to demand justice.
They brought with them ritual hunting bows and performed the waita, a dance of the Papuan Mee Pago tribe: they ran in circles and depicted bird singing.
Some protesters began throwing stones at the police station and military base.
When the situation heated up, internal radio soldiers were ordered to “if the crowd resists more than three times, shoot them,” according to an official document seen by TIME but not published in local media.
Fifty-six-year-old Jeremias Kayame, head of the Kego Koto district of Enarotali, felt danger approaching and called for calm by asking the crowd to disperse home.
No one wanted to listen to him.
“When I turned around, a bullet suddenly hit my left wrist,” he told TIME magazine, standing on the porch of his brightly painted wooden house.
Kayame still does not know who fired, but says the bullet came from the ranks of the assembled soldiers.
“There was a crowd, there were a lot of shots,” he adds.
A local resident, Alfius Jouv, was hit three times, according to his cousin, who witnessed the shooting.
“I ran up to him and examined his body to make sure it was him,” Johannes told Time magazine grimly, who, like many Indonesians, uses only one name.
“I saw that he was dead... I kissed him.”
General Yotje Mende, a senior police inspector in Papua, told reporters that his officers were just “protecting” their base because it was under attack.
“We have to defend ourselves when people threaten to kill us,” Papua Police Commissioner Pujo Sulistiyo said in 2015.
“It’s a matter of life and death.”
According to Human Rights Watch, five young protesters were killed and many more wounded.
News of the killings did not reach Jakarta until the following day.
Three weeks later, Jokovi delivered a fervent speech in Jayapura, expressing condolences to the families of the victims and vowing to address the issue of historical abuses of power in Papua.
“I want this situation to be resolved immediately so that it never happens again in the future,” he said.
In October 2016, Security Minister Wiranto said he would establish a non-judicial organization to end historic human rights violations.
But almost immediately there were excuses.
“Most of the violations happened a long time ago.
Some of them took place in the nineties or at the beginning of zero.
The fact is that we certainly want to deal with these violations, but there are procedures that need to be followed,” he said.
Wiranto then withdrew his words, speaking to TIME magazine on June 5 in Jakarta, and said he had no plans to set up an organization to deal with complaints in Papua.
Instead, he said, “Everything will be decided through a court of law.”
Wiranto, who has been accused by the United Nations of "crimes against humanity" in connection with the deaths of more than 1,000 people during East Timor's bloody independence vote in 1999, said 11 cases of human rights violations in Papua had already been settled, including the Paniai incident.
The families of the victims from Paniai met such statements with grim mistrust.
“I’ve been questioned four times in the last three years, but there’s been absolutely no change,” says Johannes.
“I am tired.”
He says that years later he still lives in fear.
“I’m scared,” he says.
“I’m afraid the military will arrest me, I’m afraid I’ll be shot.”
His brother Jacobus also expressed the opinion that the inhabitants of Paniai are afraid to discuss the incident.
He said he was beaten by the military after he helped bury four victims.
“After we buried the bodies, the military came after me,” he says.
The shooting did not stop.
On Tuesday, Indonesian police fired on villagers in the neighbouring Paniai district of Deiyai.
In a clash between villagers and a construction company manager who refused to help take the unconscious man to the hospital, one person was killed and 17 others were injured, including children.
A man, twenty-four-year-old Ravianus Dove, who drowned while fishing in a nearby river, died on the way to the hospital.
Angry villagers protested in front of a construction site office owned by the company.
According to police, villagers threw stones at officers, who fired warning shots in response.
But locals claim that the mobile brigade (Indonesian special forces) began to shoot at the crowd and killed one person.
“We were in such a panic, we are afraid of retaliation,” said 29-year-old Domingu Badia, who lives near the hospital and saw the rush to deliver the wounded.
“I’ve been at home for two days.”
The Deiyai Parliament demanded that the officers involved in the incident be held accountable and that the mobile police brigade be recalled from the region.
Paniai has always been a sick place for the Indonesian government.
The lack of significant development causes dissatisfaction of the Mei, Moni, Dani and Damal tribes scattered throughout the green central highland areas of Papua.
Many have joined the Papua Free Movement (OPM), an insurgent army that claims to defend Papuan rights by organizing sporadic attacks and kidnapping raids on Indonesian soldiers.
Some of OPM’s top executives come from Paniai, including Thaddeus Yogi and Daniel Judas Kogoya.
In retaliation, in recent years, thousands of people have been arrested and unjustifiably detained by the military under the pretext of “protecting national independence.”
Some never came back.
Among the population of Papua, Paniai is considered a "sad, forgotten place".
Poverty increases dissatisfaction.
A small portion of rice sold in Enarotali is too expensive for locals.
Bread is just as inaccessible.
People here grow everything they eat: mainly the note, as well as some fruits and leafy vegetables.
Agriculture is the work of women, each of whom can care for four to five fields of sweet potatoes.
They usually keep most of the harvest for the family, and the rest is sold in the local market.
The ten tubers of the note are worth only 10,000 Indonesian rupees (75 cents).
Over time, economic inequality has increased between indigenous Papuans and new migrants, who arrived in large numbers after the introduction of new flights to Nabire airport.
Few existing vacancies usually go to more educated and wealthy migrants.
Papuans rarely have enough money or the necessary skills to run their own competitive business.
“Young people don’t want to stay in the village... because there’s no work or money,” said John Gobai, chairman of the Panyai tribal council.
Isolation keeps Papua away from the eyes of the rest of the world.
In addition, restrictions on the work of international media remain strict.
Earlier this year, French journalists Frank Escudy and Basil Longchamp were deported from Papua for “insufficient coherence with relevant organizations” despite being granted rare permits to film.
According to Felim Keane, deputy Asia director of Human Rights Watch, the promises made during Jokovi’s election campaign to lift restrictions on media work in order to promote transparency and development have not been fulfilled.
“Now foreign journalists trying to report from the rebellious eastern Indonesian provinces of Papua and West Papua face new dangers: visa denials and blacklisting,” he said in a statement.
Lack of press attention means that international pressure on the Indonesian government is largely confined to Papua’s immediate neighbors.
In March, six Pacific nations — Tonga, Nauru, Palau, Tuvalu, the Marshall Islands and the Solomon Islands — appealed to the UN Human Rights Council to investigate “various and widespread violations” in Papua, including the shooting in Paniai.
The same countries have supported OPM in the past.
Indonesian Foreign Ministry spokesman Arramanata Nasir dismissed the group’s statement, telling reporters in Jakarta that “Indonesia still has a democratic system and a free press, so it would be difficult to hide evidence of human rights abuses.”
Locals want more foreign governments to pay attention to the situation.
When an official delegation from the Netherlands, headed by Dutch human rights ambassador Kies Van Baar, visited Jayapura on May 4, locals broke their silence, begging, “We want freedom,” according to a source who also attended the meeting but wished to remain anonymous.
Indonesia will hold a new presidential election in 2019, but Papuans say they are unlikely to vote for Jokovi again.
“The Jokowi is a man with good intentions, but he is surrounded by people involved in the Paniai shooting,” said Gobai, chairman of the tribal council.
He wants the Jokovi to know that the inhabitants of Paniai, besides living in the shadow of the threat of a greedy army, are plunged into poverty, and their education and health care are in a pitiful state.
Gobai says that the people of Paniai, like other Papuans, consider their vote for Jokowi to be a debt that Jokowi must pay.
“They don’t want money, they just want justice,” he says.
Despite threats and intimidation, the families of the victims of the Paniai shooting carried out the last symbolic act of disobedience: they buried the body of one of the victims on a plot of land directly opposite the police and military station.
Knowing that justice will probably never prevail, they will at least not let the guilty forget their crimes.
“They killed a member of our family,” Jacobus said without raising his head.
“What else should we have done?”
