EPA Chairman Pruitt Rejects Intention to Delay Obama’s Emission Reduction Rules
The day after the lawsuit of 15 states, the head of the Environmental Protection Agency overturned his decision to postpone the implementation of the rules adopted under Obama, designed to reduce emissions of air pollutants and leading to smog.
Pruitt explained his decision by saying that his agency is now more attentive to the needs of state environmental regulators than in previous administrations.
He did not mention a lawsuit against his previous position filed with the Federal Court of Appeal.
The dispute revolved around the deadline of October 1, by which states must comply with the 2015 ground-level ozone standards.
In June, Pruitt announced that he would postpone their implementation for one year to give his department more time to study the plan and avoid “non-compliance with local decisions or obstacles to economic growth.”
Pruitt, who before being appointed by President Trump to his current post, was Oklahoma Attorney General, has long been known to be a consistent opponent of tightening environmental norms.
After moving to Washington, Pruitt repeatedly blocked or delayed the introduction of norms opposed by the chemical or gas and oil industry.
The unexpected change of course on Wednesday is another legal defeat of the course taken by Puitt to return to the previous norms.
Last month, a federal appeals court in Washington ruled that the head of the EPA overstepped his authority in an attempt to delay the Obama administration’s rule requiring oil and gas companies to track and mitigate methane leaks.
In a statement released Wednesday evening, Pruitt suggested that by dramatically changing course on ozone standards, he was simply fulfilling the EPA’s obligation to cooperate with the states in a comprehensive process of timely implementation of the new standards.
“Under previous administrations, the EPA was often unable to meet the deadlines, then waited for lawsuits from activist groups and others and discussed the deadlines in the course of settling the case,” said Pruitt, who filed more than a dozen lawsuits against the EPA in his previous post.
“We do not believe in regulation through trials, and we take the deadlines seriously.
We also take our charter and the power it gives us seriously.”
However, the EPA said Pruitt could at some point again use its “deferral powers and other legal powers” to ensure that the rules “jcyjdfys on a clear course and on all available information.”
Republicans in Congress are pushing for a broader overhaul of ozone rules.
The bill, approved by the House last month, seeks to delay implementation of the 2015 rules for at least eight years.
The Senate has not yet voted on the issue.
New York Attorney General Eric Schneiderman, who led a coalition of states filing lawsuits against the EPA this week, said the group intends to continue legal pressure.
“The EPA’s change of course – following our lawsuits – is an important victory in the fight for the health and safety of 6.7 million New Yorkers and more than 115 million Americans, who are directly affected by the smog covering their cities,” Schneiderman said.
New York's lawsuit was joined by California, Connecticut, Delaware, Illinois, Iowa, Maine, Massachusetts, New Mexico, Oregon, Pennsylvania, Rhode Island, Vermont and Washington, as well as the District of Columbia.
Ozone at ground level occurs when conventional pollutants from machines, power plants, oil refineries and chemical plants and other sources react in the atmosphere with sunlight.
The resulting smog can cause serious breathing problems in people who are sensitive to it, leading to thousands of premature deaths per year.
Health and environmentalists welcomed Pruitt's unexpected change of course.
“It’s sad to think about how much pressure it took to achieve this perfectly logical step from the person tasked with protecting the air we breathe,” said Lori Ann Bird of the Center for Biological Diversity.
“We must continue to resist the Trump administration’s ideological campaign to protect those who pollute the air and their special interests.”
