Although the suspects have been at large for decades, human rights activists say the city has always known the two motives of lynchings: politics and sex.
In April 1946, a Supreme Court ruling for the first time allowed black citizens to vote in the primaries to be held that summer.
Around the same election, the FBI reported that a black whistleblower, Roger Malcolm, stabbed Barnett Hester, a white landowner, apparently because of a woman, in a fight.
Brooks says that rumors spread in the city that Hester was sleeping with Malcolm Dorothy's wife, and that the child she was about to give birth to was not from her husband.
