Inside, actors Darrius Bradshaw and Nick Ruscone, who play Roger Malcolm and Barnett Hester, repeat their roles.
The spectacle begins when Malcolm, angry that Hester is sleeping with his wife Dorothy, shouts and pushes him.
"I said, nigga, get out of my house!"
Ruscone shouts back.
It's a blow.
And at the same moment, everyone (at least all black actors) is laughing.
Green laughs louder than anyone.
"What is it?" asks Askona.
He's worried and embarrassed.
Am I overreacting?
"No," Green says through laughter.
"I just don't think white people said 'nigga' then."
“Yes,” laughed one of the black men.
"You have to say a hard 'r'."
And so the energy in the room changes: discomfort is replaced by a sense of companionship.
Everyone must do everything right, not only for the sake of the play, but also for the sake of the memory of the four people killed.
The scene starts again.
This time, when Rascona says the word to the letter "n", it turns out clear and sharp.
No one is laughing.
The show ends violently and quickly.
Shouts, screams, and then silence.
A woman in mourning black clothes stands over the bodies of the actors and performs the sad song Billy Holiday "Strange Fruit".
Her voice is interrupted by the word.
At a hundred yards from it, fifty spectators wipe tears and sweat from their eyes.
There are almost equal numbers of blacks and whites among the audience.
One couple came from Ithaca, New York, to watch the show; many live very close by.
They all endured Georgia's heavy spirits for almost eight hours while Brooks took them on a pilgrimage to the graves of Malcolm and Dorsey.
Until that moment, murders were only history, but now that they are standing in the same place where people were lynched, it seems that their ghosts are floating in the air.
When the last note of the song subsides, Green invites people to come closer and examine the bodies.
Children lean over their heads, touch the paint that depicts blood, and still bodies and whisper something to each other.
