New test results for assessing the age of asylum seekers in Sweden
The latest test results of asylum seekers in Sweden who were subjected to a new method of medical age assessment show that more than 80 percent of those tested were assessed as being over 18 years old, but not everyone trusts the accuracy of these results.
The Swedish National Agency for Forensic Medicine (Rättsmedicinalverket) began conducting tests earlier this year.
They were designed to make the assessment of the age in the asylum process more accurate, after the Swedish Migration Agency (Migrationsverket) was criticized for not being able to determine the true age of some refugees who claimed to be minors.
So far, the Migrationsverket has sent 6,880 cases for testing, and the forensic medicine agency has now published the results of 2,481 tests between mid-March and July 31, 2017.
Eighty percent (2002) of those tested were rated as people 18 years or older, and in another 25 cases, the forensic agency estimated that the subject was “probably a person 18 years or older.”
In 432 cases, the conclusion stated that the person was “probably under 18”.
Tests are carried out only in cases where the age of the person is doubtful.
According to Johan Geransson of the Forensic Medicine Agency, the results are consistent with those of previous months.
“We don’t see much difference with the statistics over the past months, the numbers are quite consistent,” he told The Local.
The high proportion of cases in which people were judged to be over 18 years of age does not necessarily indicate that asylum seekers lied about their age.
In May, the agency published the results of 581 tests and reported that in 442 cases, "the age of the test subject is likely 18 years or more."
However, after reviewing 581 published results, the newspaper Svenska Dagbladet found that in 243 cases, the person openly stated that 18 of them were being fulfilled this year.
The method of medical age assessment, which involves x-raying wisdom teeth and tomography of the knee joints and giving them for analysis to dentists and radiologists, has also attracted criticism in some instances.
One of the skeptics is Claude Marcus, an endocrinologist at the Karolinska Institutet, whose work is to assess the biological maturity of people to determine whether they have gone through puberty earlier or later than usual.
“I had reasons to think about it, and I don’t think we need to use the measurements that are being used now.
The biological age is thus very inaccurate.
If we can’t determine it with certainty, we shouldn’t pretend we can,” he told the Metro newspaper.
However, Geransen of the Forensic Medicine Agency spoke in favor of the accuracy of the tests: “In general, we can say that the risk of mistakenly taking a child for an adult is small.
The biggest risk we face is when a person is soon to be 18, in which case he is about 10 percent.”
