The order and place of the oath shall be determined by the President.
Where and how new Russian citizens will swear allegiance to the Russian Federation will be determined by the President - such amendments to the second reading in the relevant law were developed by the State Duma Committee on Legislation and State Building.
A week ago, deputies planned to directly determine the procedure for taking an oath in the law.
From the solemn oath will be released children under 18 years of age, as well as incapacitated, follows from the amended text of amendments to the bill "On citizenship of the Russian Federation" (at the disposal of "Izvestia"), which the Committee will consider before the second reading on July 11 at its meeting.
The idea of introducing an oath when entering the Russian Federation instead of formally signing documents was supported by President Vladimir Putin on June 6 during a meeting with the Speaker of the State Duma Vyacheslav Volodin.
Deputies formalized this idea in the form of an amendment to the second reading of the bill, providing for the cancellation of the decision on the granting of citizenship to those who were subsequently convicted of a number of crimes of a terrorist or extremist nature: for example, for public appeals to terrorism or its public justification in the media or on the Internet (part 2 of Article 205.2 of the Criminal Code).
According to the bill, its logic was as follows: when issuing citizenship documents, a person signs under the promise to comply with Russian legislation - taking the path of extremism, he breaks this promise.
The draft law was submitted to the State Duma in April by the leaders of the Duma factions Vladimir Vasiliev ("United Russia"), Gennady Zyuganov (CPRF), Vladimir Zhirinovsky (LDPR), Sergei Mironov ("Fair Russia") and Speaker of the State Duma Vyacheslav Volodin.
On May 19, the deputies adopted it in the first reading.
Last week, the DG Committee on State Building and Legislation approved the text of the bill for the second reading, but now it has been reworked again.
Now it says that the procedure for taking the oath will be established by the President of the Russian Federation.
Earlier, parliamentarians were going to describe the procedure directly in the law "On citizenship of the Russian Federation", indicating that the ceremony should be held in a solemn atmosphere in front of the state coat of arms and the flag of Russia in the presence of a representative of the Ministry of Internal Affairs.
However, it was not clear from the text of the bill where such an event should take place - the list of places where the coat of arms of the Russian Federation can be placed is regulated by the relevant federal constitutional law.
These include courts, cabinets of heads of bodies of state power of subjects, municipalities, judges, prosecutors, heads of federal executive bodies, etc.
Most likely, it could also be logs.
Those wishing to obtain Russian citizenship will take a solemn oath after officials check their documents.
But the Russian passport a person will receive only after he takes the oath, follows from the amended text.
A week ago, the draft said that the oath should precede the signing of the decree.
The updated text says that Russia will swear by 18 years, and not by 14.
The rule has been retained, according to which incapacitated or limited incapacitated persons will be exempted from taking the oath, as well as those who are unable to pronounce, read or sign the oath text by themselves.
In addition, the President of the Russian Federation has the right to exempt "other persons" from this procedure.
Also, the updated draft law stipulates a special procedure for admission to Russian citizens of residents of Ukraine who are considered native speakers of the Russian language.
They will have to officially renounce Ukrainian citizenship, submitting an appropriate application to the authorized body of Ukraine.
A notarized copy of the application will need to be handed over to Russian officials.
Renunciation of “foreign” citizenship, as it is now, will not be required if it is provided for in an international treaty or if it is impossible “for reasons beyond the control of the person”.
The relevant amendment to the law was proposed by a group of deputies, including the first Deputy Speaker of the General Directorate Ivan Melnikov (CPRF), Natalia Poklonskaya, Pavel Krasheninnikov and Ayrat Farrahov (all - "United Russia").
I think many of you know that getting a certificate from Ukraine is unrealistic, simply impossible.
Accordingly, many people are waiting for the decision of their fate on the citizenship of the Russian Federation, - said the head of the Duma Committee on state building and legislation Pavel Krasheninnikov (EP).
In addition, the text clarified that restrictions on the occupation of certain positions for foreigners will not apply to those who have written to renounce “other” citizenship and handed over the previous passport in the Ministry of Internal Affairs of Russia, but “for reasons beyond his control” he has not ceased to be considered a citizen of another country.
Currently, foreigners are forbidden to hold positions in the municipal service, to be hired for objects and organizations whose activities are related to ensuring the security of Russia.
Also, a person with dual citizenship or a residence permit of another country may not become a deputy of the State Duma or a member of the Federation Council.
It is planned that the law should enter into force on September 1, 2017, by which time the necessary by-laws should be ready.
