Judges to be protected from presidents
The Presidential Human Rights Council (HRC) on behalf of Vladimir Putin has developed proposals to strengthen the independence of the judiciary.
The Human Rights Council proposes to limit the powers of the presidents of the courts and to introduce their electiveness.
For the courts of appeal and cassation, the HRC wants to introduce special districts that will not be tied to the administrative-territorial division in the Russian Federation.
The Supreme Court should also submit its proposals within the framework of the presidential mandate.
The Human Rights Council has finalized proposals that will strengthen the independence of the Russian judiciary.
This work was carried out by the Human Rights Council on behalf of Vladimir Putin on January 3, 2017, which the President gave after a meeting with the members of the Council.
At the meeting with the members of the council on December 8, 2016, individual cases of judicial arbitrariness were discussed, as well as problems of public control in places of detention of citizens (see Kommersant from December 9, 2016).
The work of the Human Rights Council resulted in 25 proposals, which concern both the issues of ensuring the independence of judges and the detection of judicial errors, as well as the financing of courts and legal education.
One of the ideas of the Kremlin’s human rights defenders is to limit the powers of the presidents of the courts in order to increase the independence of other judges.
If a candidate for the position of judge has successfully passed the competition and has received the support of the judicial community, the President of the court, in the opinion of the Human Rights Council, must present him for appointment, without having the right to refuse, as the law now allows.
It is also proposed that the President be deprived of the right to distribute cases among the judges.
To do this, experts admit, may be a specially written computer program.
Also, the HRC believes that the chairman has no right to "predetermine the results of the qualification attestation of the judge, initiate his bringing to disciplinary responsibility, make decisions on the establishment of additional material payments."
At the same time, the Presidential Council considers it necessary to move to the "election of the presidents of the courts by the judges themselves" and "to give them powers for a relatively short period with mandatory rotation".
Now all presidents of courts (from republican to district) are appointed for six years by the President on the proposal of the Chairman of the Supreme Court of the Russian Federation.
In order to protect judges from pressure from regional administrations, the Human Rights Council proposes to reorganize the appeal and cassation in the courts of general jurisdiction.
Now their structure is tied to the administrative-territorial division in the Russian Federation.
The Human Rights Council says that "it is necessary to ensure the organization of separate courts of appeal and cassation instances not at the level of regional judicial bodies in subjects of the Russian Federation, but in judicial districts."
Experts take as a basis the practice of arbitration courts.
There are "judicial districts" that do not coincide with the administrative division in the Russian Federation, but guarantee greater independence from regional officials who find it difficult to use the "telephone right".
The Human Rights Council proposes to strengthen the judges of the people in order to consider some “categories of civil and administrative cases” with their participation.
For example, on deprivation of parental rights, on restoration at work, on protection of honor and dignity, on deprivation of driver's license, etc.
"These are just our proposals," explained the member of the Human Rights Council, retired judge of the Constitutional Court Tamara Morshchakova.
She also recalled that the president’s instructions were not only for the Human Rights Council, but also for the Supreme Court, which has not yet disclosed its proposals.
There is still time for the execution of the assignment by the Armed Forces (among the co-executors - the Prosecutor General's Office and the Ombudsman for Human Rights in the Russian Federation).
To report to Vladimir Putin on how effectively the independence of justice is ensured in the Russian Federation, the Chairman of the Armed Forces Vyacheslav Lebedev must by September 1.
Living a High Life: Half-floor and cunning design techniques have turned this small apartment in Earls Court into a spacious dwelling
Joan Lee, a former real estate banker, moved from a spacious house in Knightsbridge to an apartment in Earls Court in 2014.
The apartment is located on the ground floor of a cute Queen Anne-style model house, and in favor of the new design says that Joan did not pack her things and did not move again.
“I used to live with my ex in Knightsbridge in a much larger area,” Joan says.
“I was looking for something comparable for my money.
I was shown this apartment in Earls Court, and it had the same high ceilings.
I fell in love with her and offered the price the same day.”
Since the first view, the 1,000-square-foot apartment has undergone a complete renovation.
Initially, it was a one-bedroom apartment with a complex layout – to get into the bedroom, you had to go through the kitchen – and Joanna wanted to add storage space and a half-floor to squeeze the maximum benefit from the generous height of the ceilings.
“I wanted high ceilings, big windows, lots of light.
Those were my demands,” she says.
For this purpose, she hired Erfan Azadi from Notting Hill’s Duck & Shed architectural and design studio to use 12.5-foot-high ceilings to create a dwelling that would not only be a successful project, but fit Joan for life.
The ceiling was not high enough to accommodate two rooms above each other, so the architectural challenge was to create a half-floor where one could stand in full height.
Erfan had to think creatively to cope with the brief.
“Working with steel structures is very difficult,” he explains.
“We had to arrange the rooms so that they were above each other, and did not have to bend.
It was necessary not only to build a simple platform, but also to bend the structures so that they were at the right height and allowed to use the rooms from above and from below.
This solution allowed Erfan to arrange two full-size rooms one above the other in a dedicated space – and much more interesting.
From the half-floor through the vintage copper light window from "Retrouvius" offers a view of the chic living room below.
Mirror furniture with gold finishes, silver accents and vintage lighting fixtures from Serge Mui set the style of the project.
The use of mirrors plays a role in adding spectacle, space and light.
The short corridor is framed by mirrors to make it look longer.
In the kitchen, a mirrored protective panel looks like a window to another room.
At the entrance, mirror cabinets are used to store all Joan's dishes.
To create a feeling of more luxurious space, the beauty of the living room can enclose the kitchen when it is not used.
There is nothing new in kitchens.
The uniqueness of this kitchen is that it is a sliding up door, like in a garage.
"Engineering art was involved here," Erfan tells about the steel-reinforced wood-fiber shield door.
“It’s equipped with a counterweight, so when you push the door up, it slides very easily.”
Thanks to the reasonable use of space and storage space, Joan received an additional 16 square meters, an additional bedroom and an improved layout.
“After all, the floor area is exactly what you’re going to sell, that is, what your property is valued for,” Erfan says.
“Roughly speaking, a real estate agent will come in and make calculations based on the floor area.”
Here they were able to increase the area of the floors, using quality materials that give the space a shade of luxury.
“Materials are what we touch, so they help create an emotional bond with the home,” Erfan says.
“No one falls in love with wiring in walls.
It’s important, but it doesn’t touch the strings of our hearts.”
This is evidence that due to good design and increased footage, an apartment can turn from something ordinary into something amazing.
In fact, like Joan, you can choose to stay.
Government Approves Establishment of Cultural Policy Commission
The Russian government has approved the creation of a commission on state cultural policy.
The relevant decree is published on the government's website.
