The brothers are fighting for a real estate empire worth more than $ 500 million
Two brothers fight for one of Victoria’s largest real estate empires worth more than $500 million – forty years after their Italian ancestors founded the dynasty.
Former Carlton Football Club director and developer Colin de Lutis lives in Turac Palace three doors away from his younger brother Paul, who has filed a lawsuit against him in the Supreme Court over the division of property and assets.
Paul wants to quit the family business since 2014, but the Supreme Court is still arguing over the terms of the divorce.
Together with their mother Anna, the brothers own 87 properties worth more than half a billion dollars, bought since their family bought a store on Smith Street in Collingwood in 1973.
There, the family founded Westco Jeans, which grew into a network of 160 outlets.
It was sold in 1999 for $85 million.
The money was invested in real estate, and the list of De Lutis family properties today includes office buildings, development sites in Brunswick and Sorrento, apartments on the Gold Coast and Mount Buller, and shopping malls in the suburbs.
Under an agreement with his late father, Colin - whom Paul describes as "the main driving force and dominant personality" of the De Lutis family - owns about two-thirds of the company's assets, and Paul owns about one-third.
According to the court, this means that Colin's property is 316 million and Paul's is 176 million.
The division of property and money became a stumbling block for Paul.
“The section proposed by Colin gives him, in my opinion, the best pieces of property,” he wrote in his first testimony in 2015.
Last Friday, after several unsuccessful attempts at reconciliation, the first hearings in the Supreme Court took place.
The brothers are now arguing over who will control the existing business - from which, according to Paul, Colin excluded him.
Colin claims that this is not the case, but accuses Paul of incompetent management of some facilities.
In testimony given by Colin at the start of the trial, he says he hopes the dispute will be resolved.
“My Italian roots make me consider family a top priority,” he wrote.
Trial costs are rising like a snowball: hundreds of pages of depositions, emails, and reports from companies like Deloitte, Pitcher Partners, and Charter Keck Cramer are attached to the case; both sides have attracted some of the best-known lawyers, including the royal attorney Allan Myers, and the best shredders.
Mrs. De Lutis and her late husband Luigi were immigrants from Italy; from the late 1950s they ran dairy bars and gourmets, and in the early 1970s they bought a store in Brunswick.
Under financial guarantees, they bought a store in Collingwood, where Colin opened the first family jeans store.
Colin says he started Westco when he was "in the last grades of school and Paul was a boy (about 10 years old) at the time."
Anna De Lutis says she and Luigi, who died in 2012, hoped to hand over their possessions to their sons without conflict.
“Luigi often told me he didn’t want the brothers to go to court,” she wrote.
Two other brothers, Mark and Luke, are no longer part of the De Lutis group of companies; Colin says Mark received $10 million when he left the business, and Luke received $26 million.
According to Paul, both Luke and Mark were "unhappy with the financial conditions of their department".
Colin was not a public figure, although he was a former member of the AFL club's board of directors and, according to Eddie McGuire's 2015 biography, the star's best friend.
Fairfax Media contacted Colin and Paul and their lawyers on Friday.
Colin responded by texting, saying that since the case had not yet been tried in court, “I really have nothing to say.”
“I am very, very sorry that my brother Paul has decided to sue me and shout out the name of our family in court,” he wrote.
In mid-2016, Colin wrote in his testimony that he was trying to satisfy his brother’s demands.
“Our father would not like to see Paul and I arguing in court,” he said, adding that he “still hopes for a solution to the conflict.”
On Friday, that hope seems to have dissipated.
"Our case will soon be decided by the court," Colin wrote.
The new head of the Trump administration plans to limit the flow of information to the president.
Others tried and failed.
Maybe John F. Kelly can do it.
In that case, he will be the first.
Politico reports that the new White House chief of staff plans to limit the flow of information coming to President Trump, including news reports from the media, in the hope of keeping the chief in a more calm state.
This is what reporter Josh Dawes reports.
“At a meeting hosted by the new White House Chief of Staff John F. Kelly with the administration on his first working day, he outlined a major issue in the White House under President Donald Trump that he hopes will be resolved: poor channels of information to the President.”
Kelly told employees that information should pass through him — in paper form or through briefings — because the president would be better at making decisions if he got the right information.
Kelly’s diagnosis is absolutely correct, but others have already failed in trying to subdue Trump by tracking the flow of information to him.
President Trump’s relationship with television developed decades ago – and now that he’s in the White House, his habit of watching TV is still strong.
“When Trump, as a candidate, was outraged by the unfair coverage of the campaign, it was helpful to show him that he was getting fair coverage in newspapers that could be re-convinced,” Sam Nanberg, a former campaign adviser, told Politico in February.
Tara Palmeri then wrote in Politico that “according to six former campaigners, in order to control Trump’s habit of tweeting, it was necessary to ensure that there was a constant stream of praise in the information coming to him personally.”
Okay. Okay.
But the idea that Trump’s habit of tweeting was ever “under control” is simply ridiculous.
Perhaps these election campaign members know something we don’t know – for example, that without them, Trump’s tweets would be even more provocative.
We may never know about tweets that Trump didn’t post.
If his employees saved him from trouble at least a few times, their efforts were not in vain.
But no one has always been able to keep Trump from pouring oil on the fire.
Part of the problem is that in the White House, divided into rival factions, people are constantly trying to advance their agenda by providing Trump with material—reliable or not—that confirms their views.
Politico wrote in May about the tendency of advisers to constantly give dubious information to the president.
Here is an example described by reporter Shane Goldmacher:
“Trump’s current and former employees say that Trump can react very sharply to negative press reports, especially those containing dangerous leaks, and will not rest until he finds out who was behind them.
This happened at the end of February, when someone submitted to the president a printout of an article from GotNews.com, the website of Internet provocateur Charles C. Johnson, in which deputy head of the office Katie Welsh was accused of being "behind a number of leaks" in the White House.
It doesn’t matter if Johnson is banned forever on Twitter for aggressive behavior, if he hasn’t presented specific facts, or if in the past he has launched false accusations and then dropped them.
Trump read the article and started asking about Welsh.”
Goldmacher adds that the then head of the cabinet, Reines Priebus, and the secretary of the cabinet, Rob Porter, were “trying to build a system to manage the flow of papers that Trump receives and document them.”
How did it work?
Three months later, Kelly tries to do the same.
He may prove to be a more effective manager than Priebus, but Trump is still impulsive, and his aides are still fighting each other for influence.
These constant factors make Kelly’s task very difficult.
Tyumen prosecutor’s office fights HIV dissident
The prosecutor’s office challenged the decision of the Kalininsky district court of Tyumen, which terminated the criminal case against a local resident whose young daughter died of HIV.
According to the investigation, the child died because the mother is an HIV dissident and refused treatment.
However, the court released her from responsibility in connection with reconciliation with the victim's father.
The prosecution believes that the crime cannot be left unpunished, so as not to set a precedent for other HIV dissidents.
The case against a resident of Tyumen was initiated under part 1 of Article 109 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation (cause of death by negligence) in April - after her three-year-old daughter died of HIV infection in stage 4.
According to prosecutors, the mother herself is HIV-infected.
"The woman did not treat herself and refused to treat her daughter, believing that HIV does not exist," the prosecutor's office of the Tyumen region said.
The criminal case was filed in the Kalininsky district court of Tyumen, which on July 25 decided to terminate it.
The petition was filed by the father of the deceased girl, explaining that "he forgave his wife, she has no complaints to her, she atone for the damage and apologized."
The Prosecutor ' s Office disagreed with the court ' s decision and appealed, demanding that the decision to dismiss the case be overturned and sent for a new hearing.
The girl has died, and it is impossible to compensate for the damage caused by the crime.
The HIV-infected mother, contrary to the recommendations of doctors, refused to examine the baby and treat her from a dangerous infection," the press service of the prosecutor's office said.
According to the supervisory authority, she should be punished, otherwise her example will be followed by other HIV dissidents.
As told in the Tyumen AIDS Center, now in the Tyumen region about 12 children with HIV do not receive medical care because of the refusal of parents.
"And this situation has already improved - for a year of work of a special group, half of parents who categorically refused to treat children from HIV, changed their opinion - allowed to conduct a diagnosis, began to take drugs," - said the press secretary of the Center for AIDS Elena Loseva.
According to her, it is impossible to influence parents in a legislative way, and as a result, not all HIV-infected children can be detected - mothers do not allow them to be examined, hide, run away with children from hospitals.
The Dangers of HIV Dissidents
At the end of last year, St. Petersburg sociologists presented the results of the first study of the so-called HIV dissident movement in Russia.
HIV dissidents are people who deny the existence of HIV and refuse to take medication.
Doctors and activists of AIDS service NGOs call such views anti-medical, and in their dissemination see a serious threat.
A terrible photo shoot, which ended in tragedy, took place on Thursday, August 3, at the railway station Grechany in Khmelnitsky.
