The gypsies crossed the trench and returned to the “street of millionaires”
Some of the West Midlands' wealthiest homeowners are again in conflict with the determined Gypsies, who have crossed a moat dug by municipal authorities to retake the field near their homes.
Gypsies parked 20 houses on wheels in a field bordering the rich Solihalla street, which received the joking name of “the street of millionaires”.
Having brought with them horses, infants and many houses on wheels, they returned after being expelled no further than in May, and were not prevented by a moat dug by the municipal authorities to prevent their invasion.
This tactical company found a gap in the defensive structures and squeezed its vehicles through a section that was left unprotected to leave room for the trail.
Angry residents attacked the municipality of Solihalla, saying it was "unable to solve this problem".
An anonymous resident said: “They arrived here on Monday evening after being driven out of Bentley Heath, where they were throwing stones at passers-by.”
The municipality should be embarrassed and forced to act, because they are completely incapable of solving this problem.
The Gypsies were here in May, they were expelled, and here they are again.
More gypsies came last night, and maybe more today.
"The municipality of Birmingham knows how to solve this problem, they get long-term court orders to protect their parks," she added.
I live on Streetsbrook Road, and I don’t like the fact that I keep paying the municipal tax and the municipality can’t even put an end to it.”
One local resident, who wished to remain anonymous, said: "It's ridiculous, we just saw these Gypsies leave the last time, and here, please, this attack continues."
This time there were more, and we even saw a horse grazing in the meadow.”
A spokesman for the Solihull municipality said: “We are aware of an illegal camp on the ground near Streetsbrook Road and are cooperating with the Solihull police; we are taking the necessary legal action to drive them out as soon as possible.”
To help us gather evidence, it is essential that as many locals as possible report any antisocial or criminal behavior to the police on the phone 101.
This allows us to get an idea of the situation, which will be considered by the court when we present our case to them.
Crimea shares the champagne wine factory "New World"
The State Enterprise of the Republic of Crimea "Plant of Champagne Wines "New World" decided to operate, transforming into JSC "Plant of Champagne Wines "New World", follows from the order of the Minister of Property and Land Relations of the Crimea Anna Anyukhina.
100% of the shares of the company will remain in the state ownership of the Crimea.
