Italy is tightening the tone against NGO ships rescuing migrants.
Italy has warned NGOs that own rescue ships in the Mediterranean that they will not be able to continue their work unless they comply with the new rules governing their activities.
"If the NGOs do not comply with the new code of conduct, it is difficult to say whether they will be able to continue their activities," Interior Minister Mario Minniti said in an interview with the Turin-based daily Stampa.
Minniti's warning came a day after Italian authorities seized a ship belonging to the German humanitarian organization Jugend Rettet on suspicion that its crew was actually cooperating with traffickers and facilitating illegal immigration.
The humanitarian organization, which had only worked for a year, declined to comment on the merits of the detailed charges brought against it by the Italian prosecutor Ambrogio Cartosio.
“For us, saving human lives is and will remain a top priority, so we are very sorry that we cannot continue our activities in the search and rescue zone,” the organization said in a statement.
“We will only be able to assess all the accusations made now after we have gathered all the information and we can assess the situation.”
Italian authorities have been monitoring the Juventus vessel, owned by Jugend Rettet, since October.
His crew is suspected of taking migrants on board with whole lifeboats, which human traffickers sent directly to them, and allowing smugglers to leave along with boats that they could reuse.
At least one such meeting is believed to have taken place just 1.3 miles off the Libyan coast, according to the prosecution’s materials, the content of which was published in the Italian media.
The crew is suspected of violating the regulations of the Italian coastal authorities, which control rescue operations in the zone, rather for humanitarian reasons than for any other motives.
The Code of Conduct mainly assumes that the Juventus-class vessels will have an Italian police officer on board to monitor their activities.
So far, only three of the nine NGOs involved in search and rescue operations have agreed to comply with the code: Save the Children, the Maltese MOAS and the Pro-Activa Open Arms from Spain.
The latter said on Thursday that it considered the new rules unnecessary but acceptable provided they did not entail any “significant changes or impediments” to its rescue operations.
Among those who refused to sign, there is the Nobel Prize-winning organization Doctors Without Borders (MSF).
Minniti said the sharp decline in the number of migrants arriving in Italy as a result of rescue operations in recent weeks indicates that efforts to support the Libyan coast guard and cooperation with local mayors are bearing fruit.
"In recent days, we have begun to see the light at the end of the tunnel," the minister said.
He outlined plans for further talks with Libyan mayors on economic development initiatives and with Chad, Niger and Mali on measures to reduce the number of migrants leaving those countries in the hope of reaching Europe.
