The Russian authorities have recently significantly intensified their policy in the Libyan direction, and with visits to Moscow, delegations of the opposing Libyan parties have become more frequent.
The head of the Russian contact group on the intra-Libyan settlement under the Russian Foreign Ministry and the State Duma, assistant to the head of the Chechen Republic Lev Dengov told Kommersant what goals Moscow is pursuing in this region and who it is betting on.
Almost nothing is known about the Libya Contact Group that you head.
Here, say, the contact group on Ukraine - everyone knows about it.
And here is the veil of secrecy.
What exactly do you do, what goals do you pursue?
The contact group was created at the initiative of the Russian Foreign Ministry and the State Duma.
Its activities are supervised by Deputy Minister of Foreign Affairs Mikhail Bogdanov and Adam Delimkhanov (Deputy of the Duma from Chechnya. - "Kommersant").
The latter is authorized to work in the Libyan direction by the Speaker of the State Duma Vyacheslav Volodin.
The impetus for the creation of the group was the detention in Libya of the Russian tanker Mechanic Chebotarev (in September 2015, there were 11 people on board.
We thought about how we could help the crew.
Then a contact group of military specialists, representatives of the State Duma was created, our work was supported by the head of Chechnya Ramzan Kadyrov.
How did you come to be the one to lead it?
Since I have been working in Libya since 2008, I have been asked to lead the group.
Our activity was not limited to the release of the sailors from the Mechanics of Chebotarev.
We have managed to establish contacts with representatives of all major factions opposing each other in the Libyan conflict - both from Tripoli (where the UN-recognized government headed by Faiz Sarraj is based) and Tobruk (the seat of the parliament, which opposes the government and supports Marshal Khalifa Haftar), which controls the eastern regions.
Thanks to the active participation of Ahmed Metiga (Libya's deputy prime minister - Kommersant), we were able to quickly agree on the release of Russian sailors.
Then it was decided to use these contacts more effectively, to create a contact group.
Its task is to analyze the situation, identify key factors and players, dialogue with all parties to the conflict.
I would like to emphasize that in Libya we do not want to associate ourselves with either side of the conflict, we have a dialogue with everyone.
How many people are in the contact group and how many of them are permanently in Libya?
There are five people in the contact group.
Among them are people with experience working in security structures, including the Ministry of Defense.
We also want to include representatives of the Institute of the Middle East of the Russian Academy of Sciences in the group of specialists for the region.
No one of our staff is permanently in Libya, this is not yet necessary.
Are there Russian military advisers, instructors in Libya now?
If so, on whose side?
There are no Russian military specialists in Libya.
All the talk and publications about this are not true.
But your contact group includes ex-military...
Yes, and their presence is necessary.
For example, when we visit hot spots.
Or cities closed to us until a certain point, such as Misrata (where militia units are based, which played a role in the overthrow of Libyan leader Muammar Gaddafi in 2011 and significantly intensified in subsequent years.
We arrived in Misrata in January of this year.
We were terrified, they said that they were all Islamists, terrorists.
But it was important for us to assess the situation there ourselves, to analyze the real military potential, who is responsible for what, why there are such rumors, what is the real role of the Islamists there.
In Misrata, we met with all the representatives of the detachments that were engaged in the destruction of ISIS in Sirte (in December 2016, this city on the Mediterranean coast was recaptured from the militants of the banned in Russia "Islamic State" - "Kommersant").
We wanted to look at them, to get to know these people, to check the information that they played a decisive role in the destruction of ISIS in Libya, and not Khalifa Haftar, who attributed this credit to himself.
So what's your conclusion?
Has the Islamic State defeated Haftar in Libya?
That's not what he did.
Haftar conducted operations on another front, in Benghazi.
And ISIS in Sirte was fought by structures subordinate to the government in Tripoli.
And, by the way, we invited to Russia the people who conducted this anti-terrorist operation.
And they came - the visit lasted from April 19 to 23 this year, the Libyan delegation was received in the Federation Council, in the Duma, the Foreign Ministry and the Rosgvardia.
You, as we understand, are in all Libyan regions and probably imagine the moods of local elites and field commanders.
Do you think it will be possible to implement the ceasefire agreements reached at the end of July in Paris by Khalifa Haftar and Faiz Saraj?
Or, again, as has happened repeatedly in the past, the agreements will be broken, the fighting will resume, the parties will try to seize power alone?
A good signal for us was the fact that Sarraj and Haftar agreed to another meeting, not so long ago it was impossible.
In the recent past, the two leaders have spoken extremely negatively about each other.
As for Russia's position...
They often write and say that Moscow actively supports Haftar, many believe it.
We encountered this situation when we were in Misrata, and Haftar was on board the Russian aircraft carrier Admiral Kuznetsov on that day.
It was a coincidence.
But Misrata didn't believe in coincidence.
We were told, "You must be very brave people to come to us today."
But our task is precisely to show that we do not only support Haftar, we have a dialogue with all the key actors in the conflict in Libya.
You and Haftar were in touch.
Does the fact that he studied in the USSR twice facilitate mutual understanding with Russian partners on a human, emotional level?
And by the way, does Haftar know Russian?
Russian, if he knows it, is very relative.
But the fact that he learned from us, of course, facilitates the dialogue with him.
And not just with him, by the way.
When we communicate with the military in Tripoli and Misrata, we meet generals who have studied either in Russia or in the Soviet Union.
And they speak Russian very well.
And they are drawn to Russia, to some extent nostalgic for it.
Do you believe that the arms embargo against Libya is likely to be lifted soon?
Are your Libyan interlocutors interested in delivering Russian weapons?
They are interested, of course, but, as I said, we do not take sides in this conflict and would not like to arm some at the expense of others.
We would like everyone to be in roughly equal positions.
As for the arms embargo, there are constant calls from the Libyans for Russia to somehow contribute to its lifting.
The process of drafting a constitution in Libya is now being actively promoted.
We hope that the parties will reach compromises and reach an internal consensus.
Then the elections must take place, which was also discussed at the meeting of Saraj and Haftar.
If the elections take place and the legitimate government is finally elected (and now neither party has such a status), then the question of lifting the arms embargo can be raised in the UN Security Council.
To raise this issue now is pointless and dangerous, it will only lead to an escalation of the conflict.
Recently, the media reported that Italy, faced with the problem of African refugees sailing from Libya, feels abandoned by EU allies.
Can Moscow help its Italian partners in this situation, using its ties with the Libyans?
How realistic is it, for example, that Haftar’s detachments take control of the coast and end the business of smuggling immigrants to Europe?
Very timely question.
We are actively working on this.
The Italians need Russia’s support because Moscow is in dialogue with Haftar, Sarajev, Misrata and the south at the same time.
And in this matter, the tribes in southern Libya play a big role, and they are ready to cooperate with Russia.
Is it about the southerners stopping the flow of migrants on long-distance approaches?
That is, conditionally speaking, turned back the buses in which Nigerian migrants travel?
That's what we're trying to do.
But it's not easy.
Some clans and groups are interested in keeping these flows going.
We hope to help unite the South in the negotiation process between Saraj, Haftar and the tribes in the South.
But first, we would like to see the unity of opinion between Haftar and Saraj on this issue.
The head of government in Tripoli Faiz Saraj is considered an Islamist, a supporter of the introduction of sharia norms in the country.
How radical are his views?
Will this not be an obstacle in building relations with Russia or the West?
I will give my personal opinion about him.
In my opinion, he is, on the contrary, an opponent of radical Islam.
Islamists are in the coalition.
Yes, but he himself holds the position that Libya should be an absolutely normal country – moderately Islamic, open to the world.
They are also actively fighting terrorists.
Why does he have such a reputation?
It is created by those countries that are not interested in Russia communicating with Tripoli.
Tripoli is the capital, where the legislative, executive and judicial powers are located.
There is a national oil corporation, a national bank and other state structures.
Of course, some countries were interested in keeping us out of it.
And we mixed all the cards and began to actively communicate with Tripoli and Tobruk.
And we are already reaping the fruits of this work: Rosneft has concluded an agreement on cooperation with the state oil company of Libya - NOC.
Director of NOC Mustafa Sanalla, with whom Rosneft head Igor Sechin made a deal, himself directly from Tripoli.
And two weeks ago there was the first shipment of Libyan oil from Rosneft.
What will Russia do with it?
I guess reselling.
What are Russia’s economic interests in Libya?
Plans to re-sign contracts signed under Muammar Gaddafi.
We are talking, in particular, about the previous agreements in the field of transport (railway construction), energy (electrification) and a number of others.
Do the Libyans have anything to pay for?
Well, they have oil.
That is, as in the case of Iran, we are talking about the “oil in exchange for services” scheme?
I do not know what the scheme will be, I do not deal with these issues directly.
In fact, the economy for Russia in Libya is not the main thing.
We are, in fact, engaged in peacekeeping work there.
The main thing for us is to stop the bloodshed, to help the Libyans come to terms with each other so that they can restore order and Libya ceases to be a favorable environment for the development of terrorism.
For Russia, this is the main task - to help the Libyan people and squeeze the terrorists out of there.
Do you have data on the presence in Libya (now or before) of radical militants from Russia or other countries of the former USSR?
One of the tasks of our contact group was to find out.
I met with a representative of the Libyan State Security Committee, who said that to date, not a single person from Russia and other countries of the former USSR is there.
He said that he has about 50,000 phone records of representatives of Islamist and radical groups (in Libya. - "Kommersant") and the Russian speech does not sound there.
Which countries are these militants from?
I wouldn't want to go into those details.
Let’s formulate the question differently.
How many of the Islamic militants in Libya are Libyans themselves?
There are almost no Libyans among them, not more than 5%.
The rest are outcasts.
Can Moscow hold intra-Libyan talks like Paris?
There are such plans.
We are actively negotiating with the Libyans, several delegations from Libya have already visited Moscow, and have declared their readiness to come to Moscow or Grozny.
When can such negotiations take place?
It's hard to say right now.
Several visits are yet to take place, and then, I hope, there will be clarity about the time and place of the negotiations.
