Michelle Carter sentenced for messages that led to Conrad Roy's suicide
A Massachusetts woman has been sentenced to two-and-a-half years in prison for inciting her boyfriend, Conrad Roy, to commit suicide by text messages and phone calls.
Michelle Carter, now 20, will serve 15 months in prison and another five years on probation.
Carter was convicted in June of the involuntary murder of Conrad Roy, who committed suicide on July 13, 2014.
Roy’s father said at the hearing on Thursday: “My family is devastated.
My son was my best friend.”
Carter was allowed to remain at large pending the appeal.
She was facing a maximum sentence of 20 years, but her lawyers said she and Roy both suffered from mental disorders.
Carter, dressed in red trousers and a cream blouse, listened to the verdict standing, shrugging her hands and lowering her eyes.
"She killed Conrad Roy with her actions," the prosecutor told the court.
She interrupted his life to improve hers.
She did not accept responsibility,” she said.
“She didn’t show any remorse.”
But Carter’s lawyer said it was a “tragic case that she deeply regrets.”
However, Judge Lawrence Monis said in his opinion that her “age, level of maturity or even mental illness did not significantly affect her actions.”
The prosecutor read out a statement from Roy’s mother, Lynn Roy, which said: “Not a single day has passed since I mourned the loss of my beloved son.
I want him to be proud of me and the way I’m handling it – I try to support his sisters despite all the pain that will remain with us forever.”
Roya’s sister, Camden Roy, said she was haunted by the thought that she would never be able to attend his wedding or become the aunt of his children.
“To lose the person who has been with me since I was born is a pain that will stay with me for the rest of my life,” she said.
This case seems to set a legal precedent, as there is no law in Massachusetts that provides responsibility for counseling a person to commit suicide.
In 2014, when Roy was found dead in a car with symptoms of carbon monoxide poisoning, Carter was 17 years old.
The case caught the attention of the whole country when it became known that he was pushed to suicide by Carter's message.
“You can hang yourself, jump off the roof, stab yourself, I don’t know many ways,” she wrote in several messages sent two weeks before his death, while he was resting with his family.
Minutes before she committed suicide, she wrote, "You have to do this, Conrad" and "You just have to turn on the ignition and you will be free and happy."
Judge Monis said Carter wanted to get attention with Roy's death, and forbade her from communicating with the press to prevent her from getting what she wanted.
Lawyers’ opinions on this are divided.
One of the few who defended Carter was Amanda Knox, who was convicted in 2007 of murdering her British roommate in Italy and acquitted two years later.
Knox, 30, wrote in the Los Angeles Times: “Michelle Carter deserves sympathy and help, not prison.”
