Audi will have to modify up to 850,000 diesel cars
The day before the announcement by Audi, BMW said it would offer to update the software in more than 350,000 cars.
The chairman of BMW said the company believes “there are more intelligent roads than driving restrictions,” referring to European cities – including Munich, where BMW is based – that were considering banning or restricting the use of diesel cars.
Daimler said on Thursday it was modifying three million Mercedes cars in Europe to reduce their diesel emissions.
None of the companies called their move a recall.
European automakers have actively promoted the use of diesel cars in Europe and the United States to contribute to compliance with carbon emissions regulations.
But the nitrogen oxides that diesel engines emit are considered carcinogens and can cause asthma.
The cost to automakers of installing diesel vehicle exhaust gas neutralizing equipment is also rising, and maintaining a competitive car price is becoming difficult.
While German automakers are under scrutiny, Chancellor Angela Merkel’s government has also been accused of indulging influential automakers and ignoring signs of the problem.
The companies are trying not to repeat the mistakes of “Volkswagen”, which concealed the use of the so-called “disaster devices”, which during testing could modify the amount of harmful gases emitted, so that it complies with the rules, and in normal driving conditions turned off.
In the United States, several Volkswagen executives have been convicted, while others are under investigation on both sides of the Atlantic.
Last month, the former head of the thermodynamics department of the Audi engine development team was arrested in Germany.
The former manager, Zacqueo Giovanni Pamio, is Italian and therefore not protected from extradition and may face trial in the United States.
Earlier this year, Audi came under a German criminal investigation involving Volkswagen after authorities accused Audi of installing the system to circumvent European emission rules and expanded the investigation, which had previously focused on the United States.
The inclusion of Audi in the investigation could create serious problems for Volkswagen: the manufacturer of luxury cars is the source of a disproportionately large share of Volkswagen’s revenue.
In Astrakhan, a visitor to a cafe paid with fake money
The police received a message from the employee of the branch of the bank about the discovery in the recalculation of funds received from the point of catering, suspicious banknotes with a denomination of 5 thousand rubles.
A study conducted at the Forensic Expert Center showed that it is a fake.
According to the Ministry of Internal Affairs of Russia in the Astrakhan region, the banknote was paid by one of the visitors of the cafe who bought the shawarma.
It is worth noting that the cashier was not equipped with a device to determine the authenticity of bills.
Currently, the police are identifying persons involved in the manufacture and sale of a forged ticket of the Central Bank of the Russian Federation.
Such crimes are punishable by imprisonment for up to 8 years with a fine of up to 1 million rubles.
