The murder of a journalist underscores that in Mexico it is becoming more and more dangerous.
Employees of the weekly Riose newspaper usually meet on Wednesdays to discuss plans to cover the latest violent crimes in Sinaloa related to organized crime, corrupt officials or the ongoing war of drug traffickers.
But today, depressed by their own tragedy, they met to talk about safety.
They were told to change their habits.
The two senior journalists discussed what seemed safer: taking the children to an office they had already been grenade-thrown in 2009, or leaving them at home.
Security experts wrote three words on the board hanging in the room: enemies, neutral people, allies.
They asked journalists to name names for each column – no evidence is needed, suspicions and inner feelings will be enough.
These are drug traffickers, politicians, businessmen, journalists who are suspected of being held by the government or the cartels, a whole list of scoundrels who make the work of covering the chaos in Mexico dangerous.
Violence is rampant, and there are more and more journalists among the corpses that multiply in the country: according to the Committee to Protect Journalists, no less than 25 since President Enrico Pena Nieto took office in December 2012; 589 people are under federal protection after attacks and threats; and this year at least seven people have died in seven states.
Among the latter is their publisher and inspirer, co-founder of "Ryodose" Javier Valdés Cárdenas.
“The biggest mistake is living in Mexico and being a journalist,” Valdés wrote in one of his many books on violent drug-related crimes.
His absence is felt very acutely, although his presence is ubiquitous - a large photo of Valdés showing his middle finger, with the inscription "Justice" hanging on the facade of the building "Riodose"; two reporters in their 30s, Aaron Ibarra and Miriam Ramirez, wear T-shirts that depict his company, his smile, his face in the olchka.
The seminar takes place less than two months after his death; journalists discuss their common trauma, their nightmares, insomnia, paranoia.
Although a special federal prosecutor’s office was set up in 2010 to investigate journalistic cases, so far only two cases have been investigated, according to the Committee to Protect Journalists.
As is the case with most of the thousands of murders committed each year in connection with drug trafficking and organized crime, murderers of journalists are rarely brought to justice.
Rios journalists insist that they will write about the violence in Sinaloa, although they are killed by grief, although around now much more dangerous.
Without information about the killers, without justice from talking about security at meetings, there is little use," Ibarra says.
“It’s silly to waste time in this seminar,” he says.
"Until we know the reason, we suspect everyone."
On the morning of May 15, Valdez left the office of "Ryodose" in the capital of the state of Culiacan.
He managed to drive only a couple of blocks before his red Toyota Corolla was stopped by two men; he was pulled out of the car and shot 12 times, probably because of the name of the newspaper - which means "Twelfth River".
The shooter drove away in his car and smashed it nearby.
Valdez was 50 years old.
He has a wife and two adult children.
Rumors usually spread quickly in Kuliakan.
But about Valdez almost everyone is silent.
Since Guzman was arrested and extradited to the U.S. in January last year, Sinaloa has become one of the country’s bloodiest battlefields as rival factions struggle to fill the vacuum.
Let’s not say that one or more people are killed every day on the streets of Sinaloa, or that the cemetery is filled with decorated two-story drug king mausoleums, which are larger than the homes of many living people.
Forget for a moment that the state of “calmness” is simply when one of the cartels takes control of the seaside state with important ports and drug trafficking routes leading to the United States.
Despite this and the fact that Valdez was well aware of the dangers of his work, Ismail Bohorkes, 60-year-old co-founder and director of "Ryodose", is crushed by a sense of guilt for not being able to protect his friend.
He thinks two mistakes helped the murder.
First, an interview with Damaso López, the leader of one of the cartel’s rival factions, which is at war with Guzmán’s sons, was published in February.
The publication could have angered the sons; people who were supposedly gang members bought all copies of the publication as soon as they were delivered to the kiosks.
The second mistake was that he did not force Valdez to leave the country for his own safety after another newspaper that was writing about the same story was seized.
Valdés was a legend in Mexico and abroad, and his assassination was seen as another milestone in the development of violence against journalists in Mexico.
He had been away from danger for so long, his friends and colleagues thought he would always be.
He was an experienced reporter at Noroeste and in 2003 he and five colleagues founded Rios, selling his 50-dollar shares.
In Sinaloa, "it was impossible to do journalism without talking about drugs," Bohorkes said.
Over time, the newspaper earned a reputation for bold and honest publication, sales and advertising revenues grew.
Journalists liked that they could publish bold reports without fear of censorship, and readers were attracted to the fact that in this edition they could read about what no one else dared to write about.
Eight years after its founding, Rios received the prestigious Maria Moores Cabo Award for reporter work in Latin America.
In the same year, Valdez won the International Press Freedom Award for his courage in investigating drug trafficking to Mexico, wherever it led.
He admitted frankly that he was scared.
“I want to move on,” he said at the CPJ awards ceremony.
The drug trade in Sinaloa is “a way of life,” he said in October last year in an interview with Rompeviento TV.
“You have to accept the tasks that lie ahead of you as a journalist—either that or you’re just fooling around.”
I don’t want to be asked, “What were you doing when there were so many deaths around... why didn’t you tell me what was going on?”
The employees of "Riodos" miss Valdez, a joker who swears like a loader in the port, a friend, generous to hugs and advice, a teacher who knew how to get around alive.
They trusted in the order in which they were placed.
He always had to wear his hat.
He was supposed to go to El Guayabo, the bar across from the office, and always sit there at the same table.
Now they ask: was he destroyed by the love of the once-established order?
His death also caused them to doubt their calculations on how best to do their job and stay alive.
“They don’t like it when you know about their wives, their children, their legal business, and their clandestine narcotics airfields.
"These things were beyond the line," Bohorkes said.
The result, even in better times, was a high level of self-censorship and self-preservation.
You have to trust your instincts.
Stay away from things that smell bad.
The problem, says the editor of Riose, Andrés Villarreal, is that “the sense of smell can be deceived... and then what happened to Javier happens.”
The old rules, he says, and others, no longer apply in Sinaloa — as in Tamaulipas, Veracruz, Guerrero and other states, where there is a poisonous mixture of lucrative smuggling routes, weak state institutions, and corrupt officials.
The landscape is constantly changing.
In the room where the employees of “Riodos” gathered for security training, suddenly it turned out to be forbidden to bring cell phones: a few days earlier it became known that spy programs, which are sold exclusively to governments, are used in Mexico to spy on journalists and public activists.
Outside, two policemen are sheltered in the shade of a tree from the 104-degree heat (40 degrees Celsius).
They were tasked by the state government to guard the office of Ryodos, which is located in a four-story building in the bourgeois quarter of Culiacan.
Some journalists half-jokingly asked if these policemen were among the 50 percent of law enforcement officers the governor himself said they could not be trusted.
A few months ago, journalists went to a mountainous area that is de facto controlled by drug gangs.
In the next issue, "Ryodos" counted on three main topics.
This is the Sinaloa murder of the brother of former boxing champion Julio César Chávez.
They also had to expose government spending concentrated in the governor’s hometown.
And there was a group kidnapping at one of Culiacan's most expensive restaurants, a block from the D.A.'s office.
It was not officially announced who was kidnapped or how it happened, so it was necessary to be careful when it came time to write about what everyone in the city knew: that it was a favorite restaurant of both drug dealers and authorities.
One of their journalists learned from open databases that the restaurant was registered in the name of a politician belonging to the ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI), which has dominated all levels of government for almost the past century.
Recently, several governors from PRI have been exposed to high-profile corruption accusations.
Villarreal asked journalists to write about previous incidents at the restaurant, including when Guzmán’s son El Chapo escaped a military raid.
A few months ago, readers would have been looking for Valdez’s column with the most reliable information about the kidnapping.
“In the past, we would have known what had happened,” said Villarreal, 46, nicknamed “El Flaco” for his skinny physique.
"Today, all channels of communication with our sources have been cut off."
Valdez’s office is now used as a warehouse for posters and stickers protesting the killings of journalists because employees have become what they never thought they would be: activists speaking on behalf of the press.
Journalist Miriam Ramirez took several posters and went the next morning to a demonstration at the local prosecutor’s office dedicated to another journalist.
Salvador Adame disappeared in Michoacán in the west of the country three days after Valdez was killed.
The body was found burned, and authorities said it was him, based on DNA tests.
Across the country, journalists began to speak louder, organize protests and write "SOS Press" on the sidewalks and walls of houses.
On that day, Director Bohorkes was in Washington, D.C., trying to gain international support in demanding justice in the Valdez case.
In a meeting with the governor of Sinaloa the day after the murder of Valdes, Ramirez accused the authorities of spying on journalists and ordering their killings for telling the truth.
After that, she asked not to be given any more assignments to cover government activities, fearing that anger would damage her objectivity.
Valdez has said many times that journalists in Mexico are “surrounded” by organized crime, its accomplices in the government and an indifferent society.
In his latest book, Drug Journalism, he wrote that reporters are not just being killed by gangs of drug traffickers; they are being killed by politicians and security services conspiring with organized crime.
The Committee to Protect the Press, Article 19, estimates that half of the attacks on journalists last year were carried out by order of the police and government officials.
“In Mexico, you die because they want to shut you up,” Ramirez says.
Of course, murder scares people.
Everyone remembers the death of blogger Maria Elizabeth Macias six years ago in the northern border state of Tamaulipas.
A note allegedly written on behalf of the Zetas cartel was found on her body: “I’m here because of my articles.”
The computer keyboard and headphones lay next to her severed head.
Some newspapers chose to close, like the newspaper El Norte in the northern border state of Chihuahua, after her correspondent Miroslava Brich was murdered in March.
Others continue to hold on like the “El Manyana” of Nuevo Laredo after the assassination of its leader in 2004.
In 2010, the Diario de Ciudad Juárez publicly addressed the drug cartels with a front-page editorial entitled “What do you want from us?”
Some journalists have left their home states or the country at all.
This is a painful decision.
In exile, it is difficult to find work, and they are still looking for danger on the streets.
And sometimes they are killed, as apparently happened to photographer Rubén Espinoza, who was killed in 2015 along with four women in an apartment in Mexico three months after fleeing Veracruz.
Those who stay and continue to work balance daily between risky decisions.
Ibarra - who once dreamed of being a poet - admits that he is afraid to write about the drug trade.
“Mexico is going to hell, and that’s why I became a journalist,” he says.
Last Friday, at midnight, when the last issue was ready to be printed, the publishers of “Riodos” were sitting on the sidewalk next to the office drinking beer, when suddenly their phones rang simultaneously.
A series of shootings between opposing gangs and security forces near the resort city of Masatlan left behind, according to confirmed reports, 19 bodies.
The war continued as promised in a series of messages from cartels found in the area.
Sitting on the sidewalk, they posted the news on the website of “Riodos”.
The next day I had to rewrite the first page.
There were sirens nearby - another shooting in the vicinity.
Bohorkes looked to see if the police guards were ready to defend them.
If they were scared, they didn’t show it.
Sitting under a huge portrait of the deceased founder of their newspaper, whose middle finger was exposed to the whole of Sinaloa, the employees of "Riodos" continued his work.
"How can you think about closing," said Bohorkes, "if on the very day that Javier was killed, the intern asked me to send her out on the street to do a report?"
Dinosaur used camouflage to avoid enemies
At first glance, it looks like a statue, albeit terrifying.
The researchers said that the first found remains of an incredible creature the size of a rhino, discovered by a Canadian miner, preserved so well that experts called it "the Mona Lisa among the dinosaurs."
It was so well preserved that they were even able to determine that the color of his scaly skin was reddish-brown – and to say that he had, in a way, a “dark past.”
The report, published in the journal Modern Biology, described it as "the best-preserved of the Tyreophores in the history of the finds and one of the best specimens of a dinosaur in the world."
This fossil is a recently found specimen of a nodosaur that lived in the middle of the Cretaceous period, between 110 million and 112 million years ago.
Its incredible good condition has stunned researchers who call it “really remarkable.”
This herbivorous thyrophorus is the best-preserved fossil of its kind in the history of the finds, according to articles in the journal National Geographic.
It was found by Sean Funk while he was working at the Sancor Millennium mine near Fort McMurray in northern Alberta, Canada, on March 21, 2011.
He came across something that seemed different from the surrounding breed, and decided to look more closely.
The fossil he discovered was sent to the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Paleontology.
For the next six years, work was carried out to find an animal inside a 2,500-foot (1,100 kilograms)-massed earth block.
Now that all this hard work has been done, the finished result can be demonstrated.
"It only takes a little squint, and you can almost believe that he is asleep," said lead author Caleb Brown, a research fellow at the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Paleontology, where the creation is shown.
“It will go down in the history of science as one of the most beautiful and best-preserved specimens of dinosaurs – the Mona Lisa among dinosaurs.”
By studying its skin, the researchers found that it was herbivorous, despite being covered in shells and resembling a walking tank, it appeared to have been exposed to significant danger from carnivorous dinosaurs.
This powerfully armored dinosaur used red and white camouflage to hide from predators, and used a protective technique known as protective staining, which is also used by many animals today.
This would allow it to merge more quickly with its surroundings and avoid encountering enemies, experts say, suggesting that it was hunted by larger dinosaurs.
This 110-million-year-old creature belonging to the nodosaur family was widely covered in print in May and is now on display at the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Paleontology.
Scientists have already studied the animal and named it Borealopelta markmitchelli in honor of museum lab worker Mark Mitchell, one of the members of the group, who spent more than 7,000 hours excavating it painstakingly.
The astonishing preservation of the specimen allowed Dr. Mitchell and an international team of scientists to document the pattern and shape of the scales and shell plates on his body.
They discovered a protective color, a common method of protection in the animal kingdom, which means that the top of the creature was darker than its underside.
Although the protective coloring is well-prevalent, the discovery came as a surprise because the size of the Borealopelta dinosaur is significantly larger than the size of the currently living animals with the protective coloring.
It can be assumed that this dinosaur was so actively hunted by carnivorous dinosaurs that evolution preferred to disguise confrontation as a way of survival.
But most modern animals with a protective color – such as deer, zebras, or battleships – are much smaller and more accessible prey, indicating that the nodosaur had to seriously fight for survival.
“The serious threat from predators to the massive, highly armored dinosaur shows just how dangerous the predatory dinosaurs of the Cretaceous period were,” Brown said.
Chemical analysis of the organic compounds in the dinosaur's scales also indicates that its skin must have been reddish-brown.
Scientists continue to study the animal, looking for information about his life, including the preserved contents of his digestive tract, to find out what he ate during his last meal.
They believe that when the dinosaur died, it fell into the river and was carried away into the sea, where it sank and lay down on the bottom of the ocean with its back.
At that time, Alberta was as warm as southern Florida, and the rivers and oceans were likely spreading far deeper into the land than they are now.
"This nodosaurus is truly remarkable in that it is completely covered with the surviving scaly skin, and at the same time fully preserved in three dimensions, while retaining the original shape of the animal," Brown said.
“As a result, the animal now looks almost the same as it did back in the Early Cretaceous.
You don’t have to use your imagination to recreate it, you just have to squint a little, and you can almost believe he’s asleep.”
The Cretaceous period is an era when giant theropods, carnivorous dinosaurs standing on two legs, roamed the Earth.
Although the most remarkable of them, the Tyrannosaurus rex, lived millions of years later than Borealopelta, the thyreophore may have been hunted by one of its formidable ancestors.
These include the Acrocantosaurus, a 38-foot (11.5 meters)-long monster weighing six tons.
Scientists, whose latest findings are published in the journal Modern Biology, believe that Borealopelta was swept into the sea after his death and mummified in clay.
The creature was found by Sean Funk while he was working at the Millennium mine near Fort McMurray in northern Alberta, Canada, on March 21, 2011.
According to the museum, it is the best-preserved thyroid in the world, along with skin and armor, and it is intact, from the muzzle to the femur bones.
On average, these creatures reached about 18 feet (five meters) in length and weighed up to 3,000 pounds (1,300 kilograms).
Their characteristic feature was two twenty-inch spikes protruding from the shoulders.
Researchers believe that this herbivorous thyreophore was difficult to tread on what is now Canada, until the spilled river swept it into the open sea.
But the underwater burial of the dinosaur preserved its shell to the smallest detail.
The fossil remains of this particular specimen are so well preserved that the remains of skin still cover the bumpy shell plates along the dinosaur skull.
As Michael Greshko wrote in an article for National Geographic magazine, such a degree of preservation is “rare as winning the lottery.”
The longer I look at him, the more amazing he seems.
Fossilized skin remains still cover the bumpy shell plates that sprinkle the animal's skull.
His right front leg is stretched along the side, five fingers on it are turned upwards.
I can count the scales on his sole.”
