How did one activist learn the answer to the question “Whose streets?”
On August 9, 2014, Brittany Ferrell was shocked to the core.
Just a day after arriving in New York as part of a tourist trip, a native of St. Louis sat on a bed in an apartment rented through Airbnb, viewing a Facebook tape on her phone.
She stumbled across a post from high school.
It said: “Police just killed an 18-year-old boy and he’s still lying in the middle of the street.”
Noticing that no one else from her tape posted this information, puzzled, she closed Facebook and opened Twitter.
There were a lot of user posts with the nickname <0x40>TheePharoah.
A rapper from Greater St. Louis was tweeting about the death of Michael Brown, an unarmed black 18-year-old teenager killed by a white police officer in Ferguson, Missouri.
He published a photo of Brown’s lifeless body, spread out in the middle of the street, where it will be for four hours.
“It’s wild,” Ferrell thought.
But death was not something new for her and her circle.
She put down her phone and later in the evening returned to tweets that people were gathering on Canfield Drive.
There were pictures of the signal tape and screaming people and a man claiming to be Brown’s father holding a poster saying, “Ferguson policeman just killed my unarmed son!”
She watched the live broadcast as a police officer stood in front of a group of protesters with a barking dog.
In another video, another policeman, she said, pulled the trigger of the rifle and shouted, “I’m going to kill all of you... animals!”
“This is an unusual situation,” Ferrel said from her own recollections.
“This is not a murder like the ones we are used to and can be called typical.
At that moment, I felt chills.
I was angry and crying.”
She took a ticket for the return flight and flew home the next day.
When she landed at 11 p.m., she picked up her six-year-old daughter from her father's house and decided that they would both go to Ferguson the next morning.
What happened to Ferrell and Ferguson for the next three years was the theme of the new documentary Whose Streets?, which will be released on August 11.
It is a story of survival and protest, of love and loss, of strength and resilience in terms of people living in a community and filling the streets, demanding answers.
As Ferrell drove to Ferguson with her daughter, dressed in a flower and a wreath for the color, they remembered the conversation they had had so far this morning countless times, "about the experience of blacks and their situation."
She recalls saying, “Remember when I told you about how black people had to fight for what they believed in?
We’re going to Ferguson now because a police officer killed an 18-year-old boy and it was wrong.”
“I couldn’t help but take it,” Ferrel said later.
“What’s happening today is the culmination of what’s happened before.
She needs to know about it, see it and grow on it.
She should not only be well versed in activism and organization, but also understand the different levels of experience of blacks and their situation, and what we must do to become free to be free.
Even if I can provide her with an environment in which she herself will not face obvious racism, she is no different from any other black girl.
I feel like I would be doing her a bad service if I kept her out of it.”
When they arrived at Ferguson, the first stop they made was at South Florissant Road, a site across the street from the police station that became something of a tent camp, while activists awaited reports of Officer Darren Wilson’s final non-indictment.
There, Ferrell and his daughter joined a local entrepreneur who prepared lunch packages.
They collected the packages and helped distribute them to the protesters.
Gradually, Ferrel took on a new type of activism.
“My activism has completely changed since August 9,” she said, noting that as a student at the University of Missouri-St. Louis, she was president of the Association of Sanitary Students, representatives of national minorities, and was committed to food justice and health inequality among black communities.
“I had no experience as an organizer.
It came by itself.”
A few weeks later, at an evening demonstration, Ferrell met Sabaa Folayan, one of her co-directors.
Folayan said she and her chief cameraman Lucas Alvarado-Ferrer "just wanted to document" the events.
Ferrell came up with the question: “Do you want to document, or are you trying to find a story to play on?”
This skepticism was inspired by numerous people, often white, who came to the community in order to benefit from its pain and resilience.
As Folayan explained in a recent interview, “We’ve heard that the voices of people who were born and raised in Ferguson don’t get in the spotlight, and we wanted to do it differently.”
Folayan had already teamed up with her co-director Damon Davis, a local artist known for his activism on death row issues.
His involvement aroused sympathy for the project from Ferrell and six other locals with whom the Whose Streets Project team had been in touch for years after Brown's murder.
“In this documentary, it’s not someone talking for us or with us, it’s us talking,” Davis said.
“It was most important to me how these people would be presented, because that’s how I would be presented myself.”
While the goal of the project was not to focus on Ferrell’s experience – in an effort to show that the movement “is not about the leader-rescuer, but about how the community unites,” Folayan said – she turned out to be the most open-minded of the film’s participants.
As a result, Whose Streets? reveals unexpectedly personal aspects of Ferrell’s life, such as how she fell in love and married her wife.
“I felt naked,” Ferrell said, laughing about the first time I saw the finished product.
“But I knew that when you do that kind of work and humanize blacks, there must be some level of vulnerability.”
In addition, Ferrell’s story re-discusses and emphasizes the role of black homosexual women in the broader context of the “Black Life Matters” movement.
Two of the three founders of the movement – those who created the #BlackLivesMatter tag on social media after the murder of black teenager Trayvon Martin in 2012 – classify themselves as homosexual.
“Black gay women in leadership positions support this movement,” Ferrell says, “because we’re constantly fighting on multiple fronts.
Black gay women have to bear all this burden.”
Folayan agreed with this statement, noting that “the movement is actually supported by black women and a lot of gay black women.”
However, she insists that "this is not a case of positive discrimination" and that Ferrell was not chosen as the film's central character due to her distinctive features.
“She was the one who awakened that energy,” she said.
“On the other hand, it’s no coincidence that she was at the forefront, because when”
You can feel its energy through the screen.”
Ferguson, meanwhile, has long been out of cameras, but there are complex racial ties between the community and the police.
Ferrell will be on probation for another two and a half years for blocking the highway during the demonstration.
She describes the socio-political atmosphere of the place, which she calls home, simply: “Bardak”.
She's still clinging to the language she learned when she took to the streets of Ferguson three years ago.
We must fight for our freedom.
We have to win.
We must love and support each other.
We have nothing to lose but our chains.”
