The emergence of similarity: the artist creates portraits using the DNA of Chelsea Manning
In the center of the hall at the Friedman Gallery in New York, people's faces hang from the ceiling on the wire - white, black and brown, all somewhat elusively similar to each other.
These 30 portraits were created by the artist Heather Dewey-Harborg from brushes on her cheeks and hair clippings sent to her by Chelsea Manning.
Manning sent clippings from Fort Leavenworth Prison, where a former intelligence analyst is serving a 35-year sentence for the famous transmission of confidential diplomatic cables on the WikiLeaks website.
The new exhibition, which opened on August 2, is called "The emergence of similarity".
It is the result of a two-year correspondence between Dewey-Harborg, whose art combines technology, computer science and art, and Manning, a transgender woman and famous dissident who was commuted by Barack Obama just three days before the end of his presidency.
After analyzing the DNA obtained from Manning using a computer program and using it to create three-dimensional portraits of the faces that people with such a genome might have, Dewey-Harborg created a deep, though not easy to perceive, manifesto devoted not only to the plasticity of DNA data – different ways of their interpretation and the inherent determinism of these interpretations – but also to the intrinsic determinism of these.
Manning, who was born Bradley Edward but has openly said she considers herself a woman since adolescence, was sentenced in 2013 to 20 episodes, including six violations of the Espionage, Computer Fraud and Theft Act.
Her photos in prison were inaccessible, so only one photo of her was known: a grainy black and white selfie in which Manning in a platinum-shaded wig, clearly feeling awkward, sits behind the wheel of a car; with this photo she began to be associated.
In 2015, Dewey-Harborg successfully completed her 2012 project Visions of Strangers.
In it, the artist created portraits of unknown people using forensic evidence such as cigars and chewing gum, extracting DNA from this debris and creating images of what these people could look like.
And then she got an email from Paper Magazine.
“They interviewed Chelsea Manning in prison and wanted a portrait to illustrate the article,” Dewey-Hagborg said in a press preview.
At the time, Chelsea could not be visited or photographed, so they contacted her and asked if she wanted a portrait created from her DNA.
In this unusual way, the artist and her imprisoned muse became friends by correspondence and exchanged several letters over the course of two years.
They even wrote a comic book, Repressed Images, illustrated by Shoili Kanungo, which portrayed how in the future the president would mitigate Chelsea’s punishment and allow her to visit the exhibition in person.
The fact that Obama actually decided to release Manning just days after the book was released was a pleasant surprise after seven difficult years in a Kansas military prison.
There’s something deep and powerful about the exhibition opening right now, as Donald Trump declares war on people disclosing classified information in the government and invents new ways to stir up animosity on Twitter that he’s meant to mitigate.
When Dewey-Harborg was asked about the coincidence of all this in time, she said that "nothing happens by chance."
In the artist’s statement written on the gallery wall, Manning’s huge signature at the bottom (with a heart instead of a dot over the “i” in her last name) calls for an end to “automatic separation based on gender, race, sexual orientation and culture.”
On the opposite side is her mitochondrial DNA, a long caterpillar of pencil-written C, G, and A.
By including 200 letters (or nucleotides, as the artist exquisitely puts it), Dewey-Harborg hoped to show how remarkably similar we all are, at least in terms of our biological structure.
“I hope to explain to people that our genome does not determine what we are, how open genetic data is to be interpreted and how subjective it is,” Dewey-Harborg said; her 2007 video work False Memories is also exhibited here.
“DNA data can tell us a lot of different stories, and 30 of those stories are here.”
The last part of the exposition, fitting in the same room, is the above-mentioned novel in comics.
On it, Manning in the style of King Kong appears above the US Correctional Barracks building with a loudspeaker in his hand.
“If they kill your speech, they will win,” it says.
“Never be silent.”
“This is a direct quote from a letter she wrote to me,” says the artist, greeting us from Philadelphia.
"I still get tingly on my skin when I talk about it."
Manning had not yet seen the exhibition in person — as the comic strips foreshadowed — but when she arrived, she would be welcomed by the masks in the center of the room, her own genomic simulacra, gathered like crowds of protesters.
This was also done intentionally, as everyone at the exhibition up to the height (5"2, height Manning), on which genetic haplogroups were drawn with a pencil.
“I used to hang them on the walls, but now I want them to look like a crowd of people,” Dewey-Harborg says of the portraits.
“I wanted them to be like the mass movement that formed around Chelsea, like the movement that stood behind her liberation.”
