Startups that will help your company not to become the next "Uber"
Amy Errett wanted to assess the level of satisfaction among her startup employees in the field of e-commerce, but the surveys did not work.
The answers were often vague, useless, or worse, insincere.
And even though she promised anonymity, some employees did not trust the process.
“He’s never been consistent and objective,” said Errett, who runs a 75-person San Francisco-based e-commerce firm called Madison Reed.
Therefore, she turned to third parties for help.
Now there is a new type of startup in the field of human resources, which help companies find out how their employees feel.
By developing and licensing employee engagement software, they allow companies to conduct rapid surveys, contact specific teams and demographics, offer employees anonymity and complaint hotlines, and in some cases allow whistleblowers to bypass top management and contact management directly.
“We now have tools like Strava and Fitbit for health monitoring, but where is Fitbit for your company?” says Jim Barnett, co-founder and president of the Redwood City startup Glint, whose analytics programs are used by companies to measure employee engagement.
Errett said she has achieved a greater understanding of what her employees think and feel over the three years of using Glint.
In addition to express surveys and questionnaires of certain teams, the product offers a heat map of the company and shows in a visual form which units have more complaints and which managers have a low approval rating, which allows it to understand why.
Companies are gradually realizing that they need to control the environment in the workplace, otherwise they will become another Uber, which was involved in the scandal when a former employee posted a blog post describing an aggressive environment in which those who expressed discontent were punished.
For startups like Glint, this desire to control the situation is an opportunity for a profitable business.
According to the financial technology portal Let’s Talk About Payments, the global governance, regulation and compliance industry could cost more than $118.7 billion by 2020.
The Denver, Colorado-based startup Convercent, which helps companies prevent and detect bad behavior, noted a small increase in interest and activity earlier this year amid a decline in Uber’s reputation.
Convertent has nearly 600 customers, including Airbnb, Microsoft and Tesla.
Recently, Uber appeared among customers.
Like Glint, Convercent allows companies to send customized staff surveys, collect confidential responses in real time, and view heat maps of problem areas.
It also provides a hotline for anonymous text messages that allows employees to report bad behavior.
And if the top manager is affected, the complaints go directly to the directorate.
“The court of public opinion seized power from the inspectors,” said Patrick Quinlan, founder and president of Convercent.
If it turns out that the company is mistreating employees or behaving unethically, even if the inspectors do not intervene, the company could face costly consequences in the form of boycotts from customers, employee outflows and lawsuits, Quinlan said.
Ruby Tuesday, a restaurant chain with more than 25,000 employees, has used Convercent for more than a year to make sure employees are up-to-date with the rules and procedures and offer an easy way to contact the company’s headquarters.
Previously, if an employee wanted to report a problem, he or she had to look for the phone number or email of the head office, file an official complaint and hope that it would be taken seriously.
It was often a frightening and awkward experience, said James Vitrano, head of Ruby Tuesday’s legal department, who said there was no normal way to track employee complaints.
Now that the company is using the Convercent service, problems that were previously hidden from managers sitting in offices in other cities or states – such as discrimination, harassment and unfair pay – can be quickly detected and addressed.
“I can approach a holistic, comprehensive understanding of the situation of employees,” said Vitrano, who leads the Ruby Tuesday risk management team.
“And we protect our shareholders from litigation with employees.”
According to Queenland, the companies began to take ethics, values and employee engagement more seriously in 2002 after the accounting firm Arthur Andersen collapsed due to ethical misconduct as a result of the Enron case.
But it wasn’t until “social media” became widespread that companies realized they couldn’t keep their dirty underwear from spreading virally online.
“Before using technology to control ethics, people used hope as a strategy,” he said.
Both Glint and Convercent offer their software as a service, charging companies a regular fee for using their products.
It is a business model and an opportunity that has received the approval of venture investors who have supported both startups.
In February, Convercent received $10 million in funding from firms such as Sapphire Ventures and Tola Capital, bringing the company’s total capital to $47 million.
Glint received $10 million in November from Bessemer Venture Partners, bringing the company’s total capital to $60 million.
These investments are hardly surprising given the interconnected nature of companies, culture and venture capital.
A growing body of research demonstrates that today’s employees expect more from their jobs than they used to.
In markets with fierce competition, such as Silicon Valley, high wages and interesting projects are just the minimum.
Employees want to feel accepted and appreciated, and that they dedicate their time to a company with a positive mission.
“When people are happy to work in a company, feel heard, and feel that the work they are doing is delivering results, they are more committed to making such a company successful,” says Nina McQueen, vice president of global employee satisfaction and benefits at LinkedIn, where both Convercent and Glint are used.
Investors make a profit when companies in their portfolio are doing well; companies are doing well when employees are committed and involved.
If third-party analytics tools promise to increase employee commitment and engagement, it’s no surprise that they find support.
According to cultural experts in the workplace, it is important to have data on employee engagement.
But the data is useless until the company's trustees take action.
In fact, if a company asks employees for feedback, it can create the impression that changes are coming.
And if the changes do not come quickly enough, or do not come at all, disappointment may develop, and employees will lose interest.
“If you’re going to ask for 4,000 offers, you have to be prepared to do 4,000 interviews,” says Russell Rath, president of consulting at management firm Kotter International, who had to see companies make the mistake of relying too much on data collection.
“Because if you don’t go all the way, the staff will be like, ‘Did you really hear me?
You don't care?
If you don’t care, why shouldn’t I care?”
According to Errett, Madison Reed, which now conducts monthly employee surveys, is able to take action on the same day as someone reports a problem via Glint.
And, after collecting feedback from employees dissatisfied with the speed of decision-making and the quality of communication, she was able to reorganize several teams within the company and introduce communication training to solve problems.
Ruby Tuesday is gaining new knowledge about its employees and hopes that in the long run, this knowledge will help it retain employees more effectively in an industry known for high turnover.
“If you don’t try to create a culture of transparency, you will lose people,” Vitrano said.
If you lose people, you lose customers.
If you lose customers, you lose companies.
