Create a novel-comic: One castle in English history
In the recent past, Scottie’s tiny castle was filmed in the music video “Squeeze,” and in the 70s and 80s served as a haven for Margaret Thatcher.
But 700 years from his cozy location in the Beale River Valley in Kent, he watched the tumultuous history around and now inspired Jamie Rhodes, a Yorkshire man with a hairspin and a penchant for historical documents, to a comic book novel.
“I think it’s so beautiful to look at the handwriting of a man who died 300 years ago,” he says with enthusiasm.
"You feel so personal when you hold this letter in your hand."
The Castle in England covers the period from the Middle Ages to the Edwardian era and tells the story of the families who lived in Skotney; each story was illustrated by one of the young British artists - Isaac Lenkevich, Briony May Smith, William Exley, Becky Palmer and Isabel Greenberg.
This isn’t Rhodes’ first book to be based on archival data: in 2014, he wrote Dead Man’s Teeth and Other Stories, a collection of British Library documents that suddenly touched his heart.
“I could have been touched by just a fingerprint on the edge of a letter written in the 1700s by a double agent working for the Jacobites,” he says.
"That's his fingerprint."
And the letters always smell of smoke, because in those days to light the fire was lit.
And in 300 years, in the future, you feel like you're there, too.
I love the archives!”
For a person so passionate about old paperwork, getting support from the National Foundation and the English Arts Council and living in a castle for four months (“I’ve gotten a little bit stuck in there”) seems too good to be true.
Rhodes spent days studying the "new" Victorian castle, going through the archives and examining the numerous treasures of the estate and ancient things - for example, the heads of hyenas on the walls or bottles lying in the ditch for centuries.
He walked through the park and the ruins of the old castle, talking to foresters, gardeners and sometimes artists who worked on illustrations for his book.
Then, at night, he “drank whiskey and sat down to write.”
The history of Skotney Castle is not much studied because the National Endowment only gained full access to it in 2006, when the last heiress, Elizabeth Hussey, died.
When Rhodes arrived ten years later, the staff were just beginning to deal with the archive, which he describes as "something that aristocrats have dumped on the attic for centuries."
Diaries, letters from the British Empire, maps showing who owned what: "You think land disputes are boring," Rhodes says, "but two families fought for this birch.
It happens, guys!”
In some of the collection's stories, the castle becomes the starting point for broader research in English history: for example, in The Worker, the hero leaves the newly built castle to join the Peasant Revolution of 1381.
“There is evidence of a riot that took place at the castle in 1380 in a book called The Knightly Families of Kent and Sussex,” Rhodes says.
“The peasant uprising began in these places, and I thought the uprising was a good start.
“Maybe they were connected?”
Other stories are closely related to the history of the castle - for example, "The Priest", which tells the story of a Jesuit priest, whom the Darrell family hid for seven years during the English Reformation.
Or "The Smuggler", about 18th-century smuggler Arthur Darrell, who is believed to have staged his own funeral by stuffing the coffin with stones (this was discovered a few years later when the coffin was dug up).
The Darrells are Rhodes' favorite family of all that lived in Skotney: "Gentlemen seem to have been a perfect junkie, always getting into debt and spending money on things they couldn't afford.
Throughout the generations, the Darrell men have solved their debt problems by marrying wealthy older women—I see them as a company of cute guys who know how to care for the heiress of great fortunes.”
After graduating from the castle, Rhodes is looking for other opportunities to gain a unique writing experience.
