I think we're all so tense that we're about to burst.
Less talk about Trump’s ability to reunite families.
I write about this because my cousin, a left-wing poet from Chicago who had long been on the knife with Republicans in her family, came to see me in New York this week.
She reminded me that uniting against a common enemy can have a powerful effect.
Under Trump in the White House, everyone she knows, including her Republican brother, with whom she has been arguing about politics for decades, suddenly and strangely found themselves on the same side.
Dinner is undoubtedly good; but I cannot help but think that in a broader context it can be quite dangerous.
Trump has breathed strength into the left, but the distorting effect of his rule could move us all to the right.
When we talk about Trump and “normalization,” we are referring to the unlikely possibility that one day we will stop being amazed by his tricks.
There is, however, an even more dubious scenario in which Trump “normalizes” the most right-wing Republicans, who, against the background of his standards, will suddenly appear to be a model of common sense.
I caught myself missing Mitt Romney’s old-fashioned madness today – with a dog on the roof of a car and a 14 percent income tax (but we at least knew what his tax return looked like) – compared to Trump, both seem very small evils.
When Trump leaves, the next Republican candidate will just have to be in his head to be seen as a huge step forward.
