Andrei Okhlopkov was transferred from the cosmodrome
As it became known "Kommersant", the technical director of the cosmodrome Vostochny Andrei Okhlopkov began to work at the State Space Research and Production Center (SSCPC) named after Khrunichev.
Previously, he was de facto engaged in the construction of the Vostochny cosmodrome, but due to disagreements with the management of the Center for the Operation of Ground and Space Infrastructure (CENCI), he was transferred to the enterprise in Moscow Fili, where he will coordinate production.
Mr. Okhlopkov will not have a replacement: the post of technical director will most likely be abolished, and functionality will be scattered across the CENCI divisions.
The fact that the technical director of Vostochny and deputy general director of CENCI for technological development Andrei Okhlopkov moved to work at the Khrunichev SCPC, "Kommersant" told top managers of several space industry enterprises, as well as an employee of the government apparatus.
"He has been working on a new post for several weeks," Kommersant's interlocutors in the industry said.
It was not possible to get an operational comment from CENCI on Thursday, and Mr. Okhlopkov himself was not available for comments.
However, the information "Kommersant" was officially confirmed in the SCNCP.
He decided to move to the position of director for coordination of production, - stated at the enterprise. - Andrei Okhlopkov set before him the task of ensuring the minimum launch for the first launch at the Vostochny cosmodrome fully fulfilled.
Mr. Okhlopkov moved to work at CENKI in 2013, having service in space troops, in particular in Baikonur, and in Plesetsk - at the "northern" cosmodrome, he held the post of first deputy commander in the rank of colonel.
In 2009, Andrei Okhlopkov became a defendant in a criminal case.
The investigation accused him of bribery: allegedly, from his filing, regional merchants received state orders for rollbacks, but did not fulfill their obligations to clean up detached parts of launch vehicles in the Arkhangelsk region and the Komi Republic.
In 2012, a jury found him not guilty.
The tasks assigned to him in the CENCI for technological development were extended to various projects, but the main one of them was the construction of a cosmodrome in the Far East.
The head of the Federal Space Agency Oleg Ostapenko in an interview with Kommersant directly said that the situation in the Eastern “was critical already in October 2013.”
The fact is that during the planning, a strategic error was made: the completion of the construction and the first launch of the Soyuz-2.1 carrier rocket were planned for the same time - the end of 2015.
To carry out the launch before the end of the year, the construction was decided six months earlier and the deadline was shifted from December to July 2015.
To speed up the process, it was necessary to go for a trick: CENCI specialists began to carry out parallel installation of technological equipment on unfinished objects.
The main proponent of this idea was Andrei Okhlopkov.
Despite the existing risks and the transfer that took place (instead of December 2015, the Soyuz flew only on April 28, 2016), this idea justified itself, a source told Kommersant at the cosmodrome: "Otherwise, we would still not have carried out a single launch from the East, but would have been engaged in construction."
Deputy Prime Minister Dmitry Rogozin, who oversaw the creation of the cosmodrome, jokingly called Andrei Okhlopkov his "space Susanin", but it was from him that he almost always asked for information about the progress of construction.
