Red meat, dairy products, and chocolate can help ease IBD.
Red meat and chocolate are considered a nightmare for your digestive tract.
But recent research suggests the opposite: a diet rich in meat protein and dairy products may help relieve symptoms in those suffering from inflammatory bowel disease.
This incurable disease, which affects approximately 1.3 million people in the US and 300,000 in the UK, leads to colic and bloating, chronic or bloody diarrhea, weight loss and extreme fatigue.
Usually, to alleviate symptoms, patients are advised to avoid meat and dairy products, but researchers from the University of Washington have found that the main amino acid of the protein tryptophan promotes the production of immune cells that increase intestinal tolerance.
Lead researcher Dr. Marco Colonna explained that immune cells in the intestine make sure that harmful microbes coming from food do not enter the body.
Cells that are able to start the inflammatory process are balanced by cells that increase tolerance, protecting the body without harming sensitive tissues.
If the balance is disturbed too much towards inflammation, it can lead to inflammatory bowel diseases.
Experiments have shown that mice that have a certain bacterium in the intestine, appear to increase the tolerance of cells.
And this bacterium needs tryptophan, one of the building blocks of the protein, to trigger these cells.
Professor Colonna said: "We have established a link between one species of bacteria, Lactobacillus reuteri, which is part of the normal gut microbiome, and the development of a population of tolerant cells.
The more tryptophan the mice were fed, the more of these immune cells they had.”
He suggested that the same would work in humans: a combination of L. reuteri and a tryptophan-rich diet could contribute to a more tolerant and less prone to inflammation environment in the gut.
Postdoc Dr. Luisa Cervantes-Barraganvas, studying a variety of immune-tolerant cells, found that one group of mice had these cells, and the other group, which belonged to the same lineage but was kept separately, did not have them.
She suggested that the difference could be caused by the gut microbiomes of mice — communities of bacteria, viruses, and fungi that normally live in the gastrointestinal tract.
The DNA of the gut cells of mice was sequenced, and six types of bacteria were found present in mice with immune cells but missing in mice without immune cells.
Mice raised in a sterile environment, who did not have a good microbiome and did not develop this type of immune cells, received L. reuteri, and immune cells appeared in them.
To understand how bacteria affect the immune system, the researchers cultured L. reuteri in a liquid medium and then transferred small portions of the liquid — bacteria-free — to underdeveloped immune cells isolated from mice.
Immune cells have evolved into cells that increase tolerance.
When the active ingredient was separated from the liquid, it turned out to be a by-product of tryptophan processing, known as indole-3-lactic acid.
When the researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in the mice’s food, the number of these cells increased by about 50 percent, but when the level of tryptophan was halved, the number of cells also halved.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragán explains that humans have the same tolerance-enhancing cells as mice, and most of us have L. reuteri in our gastrointestinal tract.
It is not known whether the byproducts of tryptophan from L. reuteri contribute to cell development in humans in the same way as in mice, but humans suffering from inflammatory bowel disease have been found to have defects in genes associated with tryptophan.
She says: "We may need to increase the development of these cells, because the inflammatory processes on the inner surface of the intestines depend on these cells.
High levels of tryptophan in the presence of L. reuteri could potentially lead to an expansion of their population."
