White House Props Cost Taxpayers Thousands of Dollars
According to military records provided to TIME magazine, the White House’s decision last month to drive a Marine helicopter to the South Lawn for an event dedicated to American industrial production cost taxpayers as much as $24,000.
The white-green Sikorsky VH-3D, known as the "Marine One" when the president is on board, became a central element of the July 17 event at the White House, which demonstrated American construction programs.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence and senior White House officials inspected technology products from all 50 states.
The helicopter, made in Connecticut, was put up next to a yacht from Maine, a fire truck from Wisconsin and a truckloader from Mississippi.
According to the records of the First Squadron of Marine Helicopters (HMX-1), the department responsible for controlling the helicopter, the White House Military Administration ordered the presence of the helicopter in a private order, or "FRAGO", just 36 hours before the helicopter landed on the South Lawn on the occasion of the "unusual" event.
“I just wanted to make sure you knew because this is an unusually widely reported event,” the HMX-1 commander wrote in an email to his boss, the first deputy chief of aviation of the Marine Corps, the day before the event.
The letter indicated that the helicopter would arrive on the South Lawn at about 7 a.m. on July 17 to participate in the event scheduled for 3 p.m. and would remain there until the lawn was cleared between 6 a.m. and 9 p.m. that day.
The letter adds that if departure from the White House is delayed, a second crew will be required for the return flight in accordance with the restrictions on working hours.
The first crew accompanied the helicopter during the event, and the guards of the unit remained close to the aircraft while it was on the ground.
From the records obtained by TIME magazine, it remains unclear whether a second crew was needed as a result.
The Hatch Act prohibits federal employees from using state property for political purposes.
According to the records, HMX-1 clarified whether the event does not contradict this decree.
“Among other things, we asked if it was a violation of Hatch’s law, and we were told no,” the commander wrote.
“It looks like you have nowhere to go,” the deputy chief replied.
"Made in America" was declared an official event by the White House and was not covered by Hatch's law.
But even official events have political notes.
During the event, the president made efforts to advance health care reform, which was under development in the Senate at the time, and praised attempts to regulate government regulations.
The use of aircraft known as “Marine One” and “Air Force One” for political purposes is hardly a new phenomenon.
Presidents are required to use them for travel.
But asking for them only in the interests of photography is unusual.
Trump had already been the subject of discussion in February, when the presidential plane drove into the background during his first election rally in Melbourne, Florida, and his Twitter account was flooded with messages complaining of his predecessor’s use of the presidential plane.
“The White House is delighted with the ‘Made in America’ show, which featured products from 50 states made by American workers from American materials,” White House deputy spokeswoman Lindsay Walters said in a statement.
HMX-1 crews often perform training flights around the Washington metropolitan area and on the South Lawn to train the transport of the President of the United States to the White House with an inch accuracy.
When Trump was at the G-20 summit in Germany in early July, HMX-1 made 58 training landings at the White House.
According to one official, the flight, made for the event "Made in America", was credited to the crew to the account of the necessary training flights for the month.
The unit’s helicopters also flew 11 extra hours that day as part of “non-presidential support tasks.”
According to the White House, taxpayers did not bear the costs of any of the other exhibits presented at the event.
A representative of Sikorsky said that the company did not participate in the organization of the demonstration of the helicopter on the South lawn.
HMX-1 does not record the budget for presidential flights, and it is difficult to determine the exact amount spent on the event.
But, according to the Department of Defense’s hourly rates for 2017 fiscal year, the Department of Defense’s reimbursement rate for the VH-3D is $24,380 per hour of flight.
The unit records that the aircraft in the air time was 30 minutes in each direction from its airfield based at the aviation base of the Marine Corps Quantico in Virginia.
The White House claims that the real cost of using the helicopter is much lower than that rate.
“Calculating the cost to taxpayers based on an approximate reimbursement rate is completely wrong,” Walters says.
“These indicative rates include personnel, maintenance and many other irreversible costs that are included in the annual appropriations.”
According to a study conducted in 2015 by RAND Corporation, the reimbursement rates do not include the cost of personnel, but do take into account the cost of fuel, maintenance and costs specified in the contract.
At the time, former White House press secretary Sean Spicer was defending the use of a helicopter for the event.
“The idea is to demonstrate this week the things made in America,” Spicer said.
“And I know that Sikorsky and Connecticut are very proud of the fact that they are contributing to national security, and that there are, I suppose, hundreds if not thousands of people whose jobs depend on it.
And I think, like most Americans, that we are all proud of this helicopter and other military equipment that so many Americans have worked tirelessly to build.
Therefore, it is absolutely appropriate to pay attention to this.”
It was unclear whether Trump interacted with the helicopter while inspecting the South Lawn during the event, but he definitely sat in the driver’s seat in the fire truck.
Inside the White House, Trump appealed to Sikorsky, joking with the press about his own fleet of products of the company.
“I know Sikorsky very well,” the president said, “I have three.”
