The National Union of Unskilled, Municipal and Boiler Workers (GMB) is concerned about the investment at McVitie’s factory in Glasgow.
The union is demanding guarantees from McVitie’s managers over its long-term manufacturing commitment at its Glasgow plant.
The Scottish branch of GMB reports that the company bypassed the question of future investments in the cross-border facility.
The factory, which produces, among other products, Hobnobs and Rich Tea cookies, employs more than 500 people.
Pladis, the owner of McVitie’s, reports that it has invested more than <0xC2><0xA3>5 million in the facility over the past few years.
The company adds that in case of any changes in the operation of the facility, employees and representatives of the trade union “will find out about them first”.
In a letter to the head of the facility owned by the company, the Scottish branch of GMB demanded McVitie’s response to concerns that funding would not be released for upgrading production lines.
Drew Duffy, a senior organizer, said: “Our union members are deeply concerned that we cannot get clarity from the facility’s general manager on the business needs and investment plan for the future of Tolcross.”
Families have worked here for generations, and the concentration of workers is great in local society and on the territory of Greater Glasgow; it is the most important pillar of decent work in the territory of high unemployment and social deprivation.
Thus, in terms of jobs, wages and prosperity, and against the backdrop of Brexit, rising living standards and chronic decline in production, the East End of Glasgow desperately needs to thrive in McVitie’s factory.
According to Pladis, “The head of the Tolcross facility received a letter from the Scottish branch of GMB just yesterday, and the company will respond immediately, as we appreciate our continued cooperation with employees and union representatives.”
Two months ago, we held a regular meeting with GMB staff and representatives at Tolcross, where we discussed a number of issues openly.
We talked to our employees about the fact that, like all companies operating in the most competitive and unstable economic climate, we are constantly reviewing our actions – and this applies to all our facilities and activities – in order to remain competitive.
“In recent years, we have invested more than <0xC2><0xA3>5 million in our cross-border facility, especially in production lines and improved functional performance.”
We are fully aware of the value of Tolcross as a production facility, and in the event of any changes in the operation of this facility, employees and representatives of the trade union will be the first to know about it.”
